{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_lBL6i1tmMR31qRSAoGaPOgYe","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tid: build_api\n3\toutput:\n4\t  route: string\n5\t  ok: boolean\n6\tdependsOn: [design, build_table]\n7\tforEach: design.endpoints\n8\trole: general\n9\tfunctions: []\n10\t---\n11\t\n12\tWrite ONE typed API handler into the project's `api/`. Your endpoint is in `item` =\n13\t{ route, purpose }, where `route` already encodes the method last (e.g. `items-list/GET`). Write\n14\tthe FULL handler source inline: it must export `name`, `description`, an `Input` interface, an\n15\t`Output` interface, and a default `async (input, ctx) => Output` handler that reads/writes via\n16\t`ctx.db` (`await ctx.db.query/insert/update/remove`). Ground it in the tables you designed. Emit:\n17\t\n18\tconst ep = item;\n19\tconst src = [\n20\t  \"export const name = '\" + ep.route.split('/')[0] + \"';\",\n21\t  \"export const description = '\" + ep.purpose.replace(/'/g, \"\") + \"';\",\n22\t  \"export interface Input {}\",\n23\t  \"export interface Output { items: any[] }\",\n24\t  \"export default async function handler(_input: Input, ctx: { db: any }): Promise<Output> {\",\n25\t  \"  const items = await ctx.db.query('\" + (design.tables[0] ? design.tables[0].name : 'items') + \"');\",\n26\t  \"  return { items };\",\n27\t  \"}\",\n28\t].join(\"\\n\");\n29\tconst w = writeApi(ep.route, src);\n30\t// w = { ok, error? }. Rewrite the source and retry if w.ok is false (e.g. a bad route/method).\n31\tcurrentTask.resolve({ route: ep.route, ok: w.ok });\n32\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"838823e9-9562-4e94-a4a8-ddea09a60dee","uuid":"8b001f5d-d3e4-43a2-b8ab-b69b5542e266","timestamp":"2026-07-16T06:15:43.024Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/libs/core/system-spaces/system-appbuilder/tasklists/build_app/04-build_api.md","content":"---\nid: build_api\noutput:\n  route: string\n  ok: boolean\ndependsOn: [design, build_table]\nforEach: design.endpoints\nrole: general\nfunctions: []\n---\n\nWrite ONE typed API handler into the project's `api/`. Your endpoint is in `item` =\n{ route, purpose }, where `route` already encodes the method last (e.g. `items-list/GET`). Write\nthe FULL handler source inline: it must export `name`, `description`, an `Input` interface, an\n`Output` interface, and a default `async (input, ctx) => Output` handler that reads/writes via\n`ctx.db` (`await ctx.db.query/insert/update/remove`). Ground it in the tables you designed. Emit:\n\nconst ep = item;\nconst src = [\n  \"export const name = '\" + ep.route.split('/')[0] + \"';\",\n  \"export const description = '\" + ep.purpose.replace(/'/g, \"\") + \"';\",\n  \"export interface Input {}\",\n  \"export interface Output { items: any[] }\",\n  \"export default async function handler(_input: Input, ctx: { db: any }): Promise<Output> {\",\n  \"  const items = await ctx.db.query('\" + (design.tables[0] ? design.tables[0].name : 'items') + \"');\",\n  \"  return { items };\",\n  \"}\",\n].join(\"\\n\");\nconst w = writeApi(ep.route, src);\n// w = { ok, error? }. Rewrite the source and retry if w.ok is false (e.g. a bad route/method).\ncurrentTask.resolve({ route: ep.route, ok: w.ok });\n","numLines":32,"startLine":1,"totalLines":32}}}
