{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_zV8wk6oSmnt6fZgnt6LH9Kwd","type":"tool_result","content":"80\t- **ROOT of the re-entry (human, after R13 — high confidence):** the report's own evidence names it — a recovered **`Cannot find name 'organize_material_result'` AFTER the tasklist resolves**. That is THE SAME cross-statement bug, now in **THING's CALLER code**: THING does `const organize_material_result = await tasklist('organize_material', …)` in one statement and references it in the NEXT — variables don't persist → typecheck error → THING RETRIES the whole call → second `organize_material` run → second automator → races app to `built:false` and doubles the specialists (9 ≈ 2 runs). One fix very likely clears ALL THREE symptoms (re-entry, double-build/over-count, unbuilt app).\n81\t- **Direction (human, after R13):** in `user-thing/agents/thing/instruct.md`, model the accepted-offer call as ONE self-contained statement: await `tasklist('organize_material', …)` and produce the user's closing reply IN THE SAME STATEMENT (the result does not survive to the next). Make explicit: do NOT capture the tasklist result into a variable to use in a later statement; consume it inline (or, if the tasklist already reports to the user, just `await` it and give a one-line close in the same statement). Then verify the trace shows organize_material invoked ONCE and automator delegated ONCE. AFTER re-entry is gone, re-check the two follow-ons only if they persist: (a) partition still over-produces → tune `01-inventory` (segments, not cross-cutting facets); (b) `built:false` with a populated manifest → trace the automator's finalize (it may have been a casualty of the double-run). Do NOT restore direct build paths; do NOT add routing prose (exhausted).\n82\t- R14 · step 2 · L2 · `user-thing/thing#accepted-supplied-material-offer` + `organize_material/01-inventory` · verify=FAIL · inline organizer result removed the original retry (attempt-2: 4 architect + 1 automator) and the inventory reached stage-shaped scopes, but fresh attempt-3 still ran two organizer tasklists (10 architect + 2 automator), leaving 7 overlapping spaces, zero pages, and `built:false`; next round trace an L3 runtime completion/dedup boundary, not more prompt prose.\n83\t- R14 · step 2 · **L1** (THING inline envelope consumption) + `01-inventory` partition-axis · verify=FAIL (2 reruns) · **TWO big wins:** (a) the caller-side inline-consume fix removed the first re-entry — attempt-2 ran organize_material ONCE, 4 specialists, automator ONCE; (b) the partition-axis fix WORKED — attempt-3's inventory enumerated the RIGHT segments (Cairo, pre-safari, safari, Zanzibar, return). But attempt-3 still re-entered a SECOND time (2 organize_material runs, `built:false`). Judge hypothesized an L3 \"no single-execution boundary\" and stopped honestly.\n84\t- **ROOT of the SECOND re-entry (human, after R14 — pinned from the trace, NOT L3):** it is THING SELF-VERIFYING the build after the tasklist. The exact recovered error: `Type 'void' must have a '[Symbol.iterator]()'` on the statement `const [dbEntries, spacesEntries] = await inspect([dbDir.entries, spacesDir.entries]);` — THING calls `inspect()` (returns void) to \"confirm tables and spaces exist\", destructures the void, spirals on the recovered error, and re-emits `organize_material`. NOT a missing runtime boundary — THING should TRUST the tasklist envelope, not re-inspect the filesystem.\n85\t- **Direction (human, after R14):** L1 in `user-thing/agents/thing/instruct.md`. After `await tasklist('organize_material', …)`, THING TRUSTS the returned envelope (`r.ok` / `r.data`), composes ONE closing reply from it, and ENDS the turn. Make explicit: do NOT verify the build by inspecting the project (no `inspect()`/`listProjectDir` \"to confirm tables/spaces exist\") — the tasklist already built and registered everything and its envelope is the source of truth; re-inspecting is both wrong (`inspect` returns void → the `[Symbol.iterator]` throw) and spirals into re-running the whole workflow. General principle: after a workflow tasklist returns its envelope, an orchestrator reports from the envelope and stops — it does not re-derive success by reading the filesystem. This is NOT L3 — do not add a runtime single-execution guard. After this, re-check `built:false`: it is most likely the second (racing) automator run and should clear once the workflow runs once; if it persists with a single run, trace the automator finalize separately.\n86\t- R15 · step 2 · L1 + L2 · `user-thing/thing#accepted-supplied-material-offer`, `organize_material/03-build_app` · verify=FAIL · L1 envelope-trust fix eliminated re-entry (one organizer), but direct automator still returned survey-only success with zero app artifacts; L2 app-architect action routed the build into the deterministic DAG yet its tasklist returned early before `create_project`/write nodes (no tables/pages). Next round: trace why the nested action tasklist has an immediate completed `build_app` child; do not undo organizer single-path or direct-delegate removal.\n87\t- R15 · step 2 · **L1 (envelope/no-self-inspect)** + rerouted 03-build_app → `app-architect#build_app` · verify=FAIL · **THE SELF-VERIFY FIX WORKED** — organizer now runs EXACTLY ONCE (both re-entries gone), and the partition is right (4 appropriately-scoped specialists). BUT the app still doesn't build: `appTables:{}`, `pageCount:0`, `built:false`.\n88\t- **ROOT of built:false (human, after R15 — WRONG PIPELINE):** R15 rerouted `03-build_app` to `system-appbuilder/app-architect#build_app`, but that is the **standalone-CATALOG** app pipeline (THING's path 4b — \"a NEW, shareable app UNRELATED to the current project's data\"); it builds a catalog template, not the current project, so it authored ZERO project tables/pages. The **LIVE-PROJECT** app is built by the **AUTOMATOR** (path 4a): `delegate('system-appbuilder','automator', { query })` — it holds `db:schema/db:write/pages:write/api:write/hooks:write` and `writeProjectTable`/`writePage`/`writeApi`, and republishes live. Earlier rounds' automator path DID create tables (cost_items, itinerary_legs, …) — it just didn't write PAGES / mark built (survey-only).\n89\t- **Direction (human, after R15):** in `organize_material/03-build_app.md`, REVERT the delegate target to the **automator** (path 4a, live-project), NOT `app-architect#build_app` (catalog). Keep the single-statement `currentTask.resolve(await delegate('system-appbuilder','automator', { query, attachmentIds }).then(app => ({ ok: app.ok===true, detail: … })))` shape. The query must ask the automator to build the FULL live-project app for the supplied material — tables AND the pages to view them — so the manifest ends with pages>0 and built:true (earlier automator runs made tables but pageCount:0). If the automator still stops at data-only, trace WHETHER the query asks for pages and whether `built` is set by a separate finalize the nested delegate skips. Everything else in step 2 is now correct (single run, right 4 specialists) — this is the LAST piece: a served app with real rows+pages.\n90\t- R16 · step 2 · L2 · `user-thing/organize_material/03-build_app` + `system-spaces-dag.test.ts` + `org/docs/system-spaces/README.md` · verify=FAIL · corrected catalog `app-architect#build_app` to live-project `automator`; fresh replay seeded four tables (27 rows) and wrote four pages/APIs, proving the handoff, but inventory still emitted four forbidden cross-cutting facets instead of independently-owned segments. The app manifest’s `built:false` is a cache-hit signal after the second automator pass; pages are present. Next round: do not retry partition prose; implement/justify an enforceable structured partition contract.\n91\t- R16 · step 2 · **L1** rerouted `03-build_app` → live-project **automator** (path 4a), NOT `app-architect#build_app` (catalog) · verify=FAIL(partition) · **APP BUILD FIXED** — fresh run seeded ~27 rows across 4 tables + authored 4 pages + 4 APIs (was 0 pages). Only the partition remained wrong (inventory made data-category/facet specialists: Cost Tracker, Memories, Dashboard). `built:false` reported as a cache-hit artifact of a second automator pass; pages are materially present.\n92\t- **DECISION (human, after R16): LOOSEN the step-2 partition expectation (L0), do NOT keep forcing an exact per-leg partition.** The partition is inherent model judgment (round 14 once got Cairo/pre-safari/safari/Zanzibar/return; round 16 got facets) and pure prose is exhausted. `scenario.yaml` step-2 now asserts only: the material is split across MULTIPLE topic specialists for distinct parts of the trip, NOT one generic catch-all (the original R7-8 failure) — the exact partition is the model's call. The load-bearing assertions stay: every fixture token lands in real state, the app is built+served, no research. Round 17: re-verify step 2 under the loosened bar. If the only remaining blocker is `built:false` while pages+tables+APIs exist and the app actually serves, determine whether that flag is a snapshot/manifest artifact (check the app renders, step-3 style) vs a real build failure — do not fail a served app on a stale flag.\n93\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"call_fzpUJSbHB3H8gLDKEI4xloQi","session_id":"838823e9-9562-4e94-a4a8-ddea09a60dee","uuid":"f433ec77-ef38-407a-8666-2befffc9ee0c","timestamp":"2026-07-16T06:18:48.077Z","subagent_type":"Explore","task_description":"Trace automator structural failure"}
