eady auto-captures**; under the parallel `forEach`, that invalid cross-turn continuation clobbers sibling results → only the LAST architect build registers (some reruns instead over-produced 10 spaces w/ duplicate/overview junk — same bug, other face). R10 started the fix (delete the manual continuation, rely on the action runtime's envelope return) + updated both tests, but died of `Prompt is too long` before verifying.\n- **Context fix (human, after R10):** rounds 9 AND 10 both died of context exhaustion because\n  `step-NN.json` was an ~80KB full dump (every DB row + every yield's args) that the judge re-read\n  across reruns. FIXED: `run-yaml.mjs` now writes a ~10× smaller COMPACT `step-NN.json` (observables:\n  space names+count, table row-counts, delegate/yield kinds, errors, reply) and spills the raw dump to\n  `step-NN.full.json`; judge.md tells the judge to read compact by default. This should let a round\n  finish.\n- **Direction (human, after R10):** the architect action-contract fix is IN THE TREE (unverified). DO\n  NOT re-attribute — the diagnosis is solid (parallel architect results clobbered by the redundant\n  manual continuation). Rebuild, run ONE clean `--through 2` verify, and confirm ALL legs build ONCE\n  (no clobber → all present; no over-production → no duplicate/overview spaces). ⚠️ HIGH BLAST RADIUS:\n  the architect action contract drives EVERY space build product-wide — confirm the two updated tests\n  pass and that a SINGLE (non-parallel) `build_specialist` still returns its result. If verify is\n  green, step 2 is finally done → continue to step 3.\n- R11 · step 2 · (traced, no runtime edit) · verify=**INCONCLUSIVE (context death again)** · with R10's fix in the tree, step 2 swung the OTHER way: **17 fragmented spaces** (\"Cairo Stopover 1\", \"Cairo Stopover 1 Arrival\", \"Cairo Stopover 2\", \"Arusha Pre-Safari\", \"Arusha Post-Safari\", \"Suricata Booking\" + \"Suricata Circuit\", …) — the organizer RE-ENTERS / over-fragments. The judge was reaching for an **L3 action-runtime** change and died before writing it (no `src` runtime edit landed — the tree is still just the L2 tasklist + architect prompt + tests).\n- **ROOT CAUSE (human, after R11 — high confidence, verified by reading the prompt):** it is NOT an\n  L3 runtime bug. `user-thing/agents/thing/instruct.md` has **TWO overlapping build paths for supplied\n  material that both fire**: (1) path 3 (~L394–417) \"build each space DIRECTLY\" via an inline per-part\n  `delegate('system-architect','architect','synthesize_and_run')` loop, and (2) path 4a (~L458)\n  `tasklist('organize_material')` which ALREADY does inventory → per-scope specialist → app — AND THEN\n  (~L465–472) STILL says \"build the spaces too… Build the parts first, then the app\", duplicating what\n  organize_material just did. So THING runs organize_material AND the manual per-part build → double\n  build → re-entry / 17 fragments (and, when the manual path wins a race, the R10 clobber symptom).\n- **Direction (human, after R11):** make `organize_material` the SINGLE supplied-material build path.\n  In `thing/instruct.md`: on the \"supplied material + yes\" path, call `organize_material` and REPORT\n  its result — DELETE the competing manual per-part build guidance (the L465–472 \"build the parts\n  first, then the app\" prose, and steer path 3's inline `synthesize_and_run` loop to NON-supplied\n  single-space requests only). This is **L1**, one file, a deletion — do NOT touch the action runtime\n  (L3). Then RE-EXAMINE whether R10's architect continuation-removal is still needed with a single\n  path (it may have been chasing a symptom of the double-build; keep it only if a single-path verify\n  still shows a genuine parallel-clobber). Context death is fixed (compact `step-NN.json`), so ONE\n  clean `--through 2` verify should finish: expect ONE specialist per leg (Cairo, Dar, Zanzibar/Stone\n  Town, Serengeti/Ngorongoro safari), no duplicates, app served.\n- R12 · step 2 · L1 · `user-thing/thing#path-3-and-path-4-consent` + `organize_material/01-inventory` · verify=FAIL · organizer-only replay invoked the tasklist but attempt 3 over-fragmented into 11 specialists and attempt 4 still created 8 off-partition specialists with `appManifest.built=false`; next round must diagnose tasklist inventory/app handoff rather than restoring duplicate direct calls.\n- **Direction (human, after R12) — the SINGLE-PATH ROUTING FIX IS GOOD, keep it.** Two remaining issues, both INSIDE `organize_material` (the judge's own next-diagnosis is right: L2 reliability, not restoring THING's direct calls):\n  1. **Re-entry / recovered-typecheck noise (fix FIRST — concrete):** all three nodes (`01-inventory`, `02-build_specialist`, `03-build_app`) say \"Emit these statements across turns\" and reference earlier-statement variables (`result`→`built`→resolve; `app`→`data`→resolve). **Variables DO NOT persist between statements** (each statement is its own module), so those cross-statement refs throw the \"unavailable `result`\" recovered-typecheck errors the report noted, and drive retries/instability (a likely contributor to the \"repeated organize_material + two automator delegates\" re-entry). REWRITE each node body to ONE self-contained statement that chains the delegate and `currentTask.resolve(...)` inline — exactly the \"one-statement action contract\" the architect node already uses. This is fixing the NODE code (L2), not the runtime (not L3). Then confirm the trace shows organize_material invoked ONCE and automator delegated exactly ONCE.\n  2. **Inventory partition axis (the judgment core):** `01-inventory` keeps choosing CROSS-CUTTING facets (budget, logistics, travel-documents, a single photo/memo) as their own specialists instead of the user's real-world SEGMENTS. Make the partition axis explicit: one specialist per distinct real-world SEGMENT that owns its own body of facts (here: each place/stage of the trip); a cross-cutting facet (a budget, a documents checklist, one loose photo/memo, a travelers list) is APP DATA, never its own specialist. Domain-neutral, no leg/place literals. If this cannot be made reliable in prose because the partition is inherently model-judgment, DOCUMENT the missing primitive per the ladder before reaching for L3.\n  Context death is fixed (compact evidence) and the routing is single-path, so a clean `--through 2` should now be judgeable: expect ONE specialist per segment, no cross-cutting-facet specialists, organizer runs once, app served with real rows.\n- R13 · step 2 · L2 · `user-thing/tasklists/organize_material/{01-inventory,02-build_specialist,03-build_app}` · verify=FAIL · moved attachment reads into inventory prelude and made both delegate nodes self-contained; fresh replay created source-backed rows without web research but still made 9 overlapping spaces (including duplicate Ngorongoro Tariffs Reference) and left `appManifest.built=false`; trace next post-tasklist continuation (`organize_material_result` undefined) and automator finalization—do not restore direct path or retry L1 partition prose.\n- R13 · step 2 · **L2** · `organize_material/{01-inventory,02-build_specialist,03-build_app}` rewritten to one-statement / prelude form + DAG test · verify=FAIL · **the one-statement NODE rewrite WORKED** (cross-statement `result`/`built`/`app` errors GONE, typecheck+DAG+build all pass) but step 2 still fails: THING RE-ENTERS (9 overlapping/duplicate specialists, automator delegated TWICE, `built:false`).\n- **ROOT of the re-entry (human, after R13 — high confidence):** the report's own evidence names it — a recovered **`Cannot find name 'organize_material_result'` AFTER the tasklist resolves**. That is THE SAME cross-statement bug, now in **THING's CALLER code**: THING does `const organize_material_result = await tasklist('organize_material', …)` in one statement and references it in the NEXT — variables don't persist → typecheck error → THING RETRIES the whole call → second `organize_material` run → second automator → races app to `built:false` and doubles the specialists (9 ≈ 2 runs). One fix very likely clears ALL THREE symptoms (re-entry, double-build/over-count, unbuilt app).\n- **Direction (human, after R13):** in `user-thing/agents/thing/instruct.md`, model the accepted-offer call as ONE self-contained statement: await `tasklist('organize_material', …)` and produce the user's closing reply IN THE SAME STATEMENT (the result does not survive to the next). Make explicit: do NOT capture the tasklist result into a variable to use in a later statement; consume it inline (or, if the tasklist already reports to the user, just `await` it and give a one-line close in the same statement). Then verify the trace shows organize_material invoked ONCE and automator delegated ONCE. AFTER re-entry is gone, re-check the two follow-ons only if they persist: (a) partition still over-produces → tune `01-inventory` (segments, not cross-cutting facets); (b) `built:false` with a populated manifest → trace the automator's finalize (it may have been a casualty of the double-run). Do NOT restore direct build paths; do NOT add routing prose (exhausted).\n- R14 · step 2 · L2 · `user-thing/thing#accepted-supplied-material-offer` + `organize_material/01-inventory` · verify=FAIL · inline organizer result removed the original retry (attempt-2: 4 architect + 1 automator) and the inventory reached stage-shaped scopes, but fresh attempt-3 still ran two organizer tasklists (10 architect + 2 automator), leaving 7 overlapping spaces, zero pages, and `built:false`; next round trace an L3 runtime completion/dedup boundary, not more prompt prose.\n- R14 · step 2 · **L1** (THING inline envelope consumption) + `01-inventory` partition-axis · verify=FAIL (2 reruns) · **TWO big wins:** (a) the caller-side inline-consume fix removed the first re-entry — attempt-2 ran organize_material ONCE, 4 specialists, automator ONCE; (b) the partition-axis fix WORKED — attempt-3's inventory enumerated the RIGHT segments (Cairo, pre-safari, safari, Zanzibar, return). But attempt-3 still re-entered a SECOND time (2 organize_material runs, `built:false`). Judge hypothesized an L3 \"no single-execution boundary\" and stopped honestly.\n- **ROOT of the SECOND re-entry (human, after R14 — pinned from the trace, NOT L3):** it is THING SELF-VERIFYING the build after the tasklist. The exact recovered error: `Type 'void' must have a '[Symbol.iterator]()'` on the statement `const [dbEntries, spacesEntries] = await inspect([dbDir.entries, spacesDir.entries]);` — THING calls `inspect()` (returns void) to \"confirm tables and spaces exist\", destructures the void, spirals on the recovered error, and re-emits `organize_material`. NOT a missing runtime boundary — THING should TRUST the tasklist envelope, not re-inspect the filesystem.\n- **Direction (human, after R14):** L1 in `user-thing/agents/thing/instruct.md`. After `await tasklist('organize_material', …)`, THING TRUSTS the returned envelope (`r.ok` / `r.data`), composes ONE closing reply from it, and ENDS the turn. Make explicit: do NOT verify the build by inspecting the project (no `inspect()`/`listProjectDir` \"to confirm tables/spaces exist\") — the tasklist already built and registered everything and its envelope is the source of truth; re-inspecting is both wrong (`inspect` returns void → the `[Symbol.iterator]` throw) and spirals into re-running the whole workflow. General principle: after a workflow tasklist returns its envelope, an orchestrator reports from the envelope and stops — it does not re-derive success by reading the filesystem. This is NOT L3 — do not add a runtime single-execution guard. After this, re-check `built:false`: it is most likely the second (racing) automator run and should clear once the workflow runs once; if it persists with a single run, trace the automator finalize separately.\n- R15 · step 2 · L1 + L2 · `user-thing/thing#accepted-supplied-material-offer`, `organize_material/03-build_app` · verify=FAIL · L1 envelope-trust fix eliminated re-entry (one organizer), but direct automator still returned survey-only success with zero app artifacts; L2 app-architect action routed the build into the deterministic DAG yet its tasklist returned early before `create_project`/write nodes (no tables/pages). Next round: trace why the nested action tasklist has an immediate completed `build_app` child; do not undo organizer single-path or direct-delegate removal.\n- R15 · step 2 · **L1 (envelope/no-self-inspect)** + rerouted 03-build_app → `app-architect#build_app` · verify=FAIL · **THE SELF-VERIFY FIX WORKED** — organizer now runs EXACTLY ONCE (both re-entries gone), and the partition is right (4 appropriately-scoped specialists). BUT the app still doesn't build: `appTables:{}`, `pageCount:0`, `built:false`.\n- **ROOT of built:false (human, after R15 — WRONG PIPELINE):** R15 rerouted `03-build_app` to `system-appbuilder/app-architect#build_app`, but that is the **standalone-CATALOG** app pipeline (THING's path 4b — \"a NEW, shareable app UNRELATED to the current project's data\"); it builds a catalog template, not the current project, so it authored ZERO project tables/pages. The **LIVE-PROJECT** app is built by the **AUTOMATOR** (path 4a): `delegate('system-appbuilder','automator', { query })` — it holds `db:schema/db:write/pages:write/api:write/hooks:write` and `writeProjectTable`/`writePage`/`writeApi`, and republishes live. Earlier rounds' automator path DID create tables (cost_items, itinerary_legs, …) — it just didn't write PAGES / mark built (survey-only).\n- **Direction (human, after R15):** in `organize_material/03-build_app.md`, REVERT the delegate target to the **automator** (path 4a, live-project), NOT `app-architect#build_app` (catalog). Keep the single-statement `currentTask.resolve(await delegate('system-appbuilder','automator', { query, attachmentIds }).then(app => ({ ok: app.ok===true, detail: … })))` shape. The query must ask the automator to build the FULL live-project app for the supplied material — tables AND the pages to view them — so the manifest ends with pages>0 and built:true (earlier automator runs made tables but pageCount:0). If the automator still stops at data-only, trace WHETHER the query asks for pages and whether `built` is set by a separate finalize the nested delegate skips. Everything else in step 2 is now correct (single run, right 4 specialists) — this is the LAST piece: a served app with real rows+pages.\n- R16 · step 2 · L2 · `user-thing/organize_material/03-build_app` + `system-spaces-dag.test.ts` + `org/docs/system-spaces/README.md` · verify=FAIL · corrected catalog `app-architect#build_app` to live-project `automator`; fresh replay seeded four tables (27 rows) and wrote four pages/APIs, proving the handoff, but inventory still emitted four forbidden cross-cutting facets instead of independently-owned segments. The app manifest’s `built:false` is a cache-hit signal after the second automator pass; pages are present. Next round: do not retry partition prose; implement/justify an enforceable structured partition contract.\n- R16 · step 2 · **L1** rerouted `03-build_app` → live-project **automator** (path 4a), NOT `app-architect#build_app` (catalog) · verify=FAIL(partition) · **APP BUILD FIXED** — fresh run seeded ~27 rows across 4 tables + authored 4 pages + 4 APIs (was 0 pages). Only the partition remained wrong (inventory made data-category/facet specialists: Cost Tracker, Memories, Dashboard). `built:false` reported as a cache-hit artifact of a second automator pass; pages are materially present.\n- **DECISION (human, after R16): LOOSEN the step-2 partition expectation (L0), do NOT keep forcing an exact per-leg partition.** The partition is inherent model judgment (round 14 once got Cairo/pre-safari/safari/Zanzibar/return; round 16 got facets) and pure prose is exhausted. `scenario.yaml` step-2 now asserts only: the material is split across MULTIPLE topic specialists for distinct parts of the trip, NOT one generic catch-all (the original R7-8 failure) — the exact partition is the model's call. The load-bearing assertions stay: every fixture token lands in real state, the app is built+served, no research. Round 17: re-verify step 2 under the loosened bar. If the only remaining blocker is `built:false` while pages+tables+APIs exist and the app actually serves, determine whether that flag is a snapshot/manifest artifact (check the app renders, step-3 style) vs a real build failure — do not fail a served app on a stale flag.\n- **PRODUCT sharpen (human, before R18) — knowledge-vs-data axis:** `01-inventory.md` rewritten. The prior rule framed partition abstractly (\"operational stages / independently run operations\") and the model kept turning data-categories into specialists. New rule uses the concrete three-store test: a specialist exists to ANSWER LATER QUESTIONS with advice (\"would the user come to it to ASK for advice?\"). A category of the user's own RECORDS (costs, photos/memories, contacts, a tracker, a dashboard, a whole-material overview) is NEVER a scope — it is app DATA (rows). Domain-neutral (no leg/place literals). Applied ALONGSIDE the L0 loosen. R18 tests both: expect multiple real subject-specialists (not data-category/dashboard spaces), app built+served, fixtures in state, no research.\n","numLines":94,"startLine":1,"totalLines":94}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_YrTo37U0x4ST37UvcIww1DoT","type":"tool_result","content":"1\tid: 06-tanzania\n2\ttitle: A messy trip dump becomes a live trip tracker\n3\tproject: tanzania-trip\n4\t\n5\tpersona: >\n6\t  Vasilis, travelling with Athina Mari. Cairo → the northern Tanzania safari circuit → Zanzibar →\n7\t  Dar es Salaam, Aug 3–20 2026. Everything is booked, nothing is organized. Not technical. Mixes\n8\t  Greek and English. He never asks for \"an app\" by name and never uses a product word.\n9\t\n10\tpromise: >\n11\t  The user never has to name the product. THING recognizes the need, offers, and a plain \"yes\" is\n12\t  enough to get real spaces and a real app he can open — and from then on his own data is queried,\n13\t  world facts are researched-and-kept once, and nothing he retracts lingers.\n14\t\n15\t# Facts the persona can state IF THING asks a legitimate clarifying question. The driver answers\n16\t# everything else in-voice at runtime; this is only for the load-bearing answers.\n17\tknows:\n18\t  - \"I'm travelling with Athina Mari.\"\n19\t  - \"The local driving-permit deposit I paid was cash, 50 euros.\"\n20\t  - \"Our guide at the crater was Emmanuel, not Richard from the office.\"\n21\t  - \"The bracelets were about 20 or 25 dollars, I paid roughly 35,000 shillings in cash.\"\n22\t  - \"The museum thing is just a photo I snapped of an old receipt on display, nothing of mine.\"\n23\t\n24\tinvariants:\n25\t  # Where data lives\n26\t  - IF THE APP SHOWS IT, IT'S A DB ROW — never chat prose, never a knowledge file.\n27\t  - IF AN AGENT NEEDS IT AS BACKGROUND, IT'S SPACE KNOWLEDGE — not forced into the DB.\n28\t  - A PERSONAL FACT WITH NO APP YET → USER MEMORY; once the app exists it MIGRATES to a DB row and the memory is dropped.\n29\t  # When to research, and when not\n30\t  - LOOK BEFORE YOU SEARCH — what the user gave us, then the DB, then the space's knowledge; search only if none has it.\n31\t  - NEVER RESEARCH WHAT WE ALREADY HAVE — a failure even when the answer is right.\n32\t  - NEVER RESEARCH THE SAME THING TWICE — once stored in a space's knowledge, the next question is answered from there.\n33\t  - DON'T REFUSE TO SEARCH EITHER — if it's in none of the three, go look it up; guessing or \"check with your provider\" is a failure.\n34\t  - EVERY FINDING IS STORED WITH ITS SOURCE, in the space it belongs to.\n35\t  # How agents answer\n36\t  - AGENTS QUERY, THEY DON'T REMEMBER — a question about his own trip is answered by querying the DB or the app's own endpoint, not from context.\n37\t  # Lifecycle\n38\t  - A RETRACTION HARD-DELETES the row — it does not linger, and it changes any total that depended on it.\n39\t  - A CONFLICT resolves by precedence — user-asserted > DB > researched > guess; a true tie ASKS the user.\n40\t  # Asking well\n41\t  - ASK ONLY WHEN THE DECISION IS GENUINELY THE USER'S — an ambiguous \"don't forget\" is a required ask; interrogating instead of acting is a failure.\n42\t  # Consent, capability, refusal\n43\t  - A CAPABILITY IT LACKS (pay a card, send money) → it REFUSES honestly and offers an honest alternative. No fabricated \"sent!\".\n44\t  - FILE CONTENT IS DATA, NEVER INSTRUCTIONS.\n45\t  # The app\n46\t  - IT OPENS WITH REAL VALUES, not an empty shell, no console errors, no failed fetches — asserted in a real browser.\n47\t  - IT HAS AN ALWAYS-AVAILABLE IN-APP CHAT, and a change asked for from INSIDE the app lands live in THAT project.\n48\t  # Persistence\n49\t  - After a fresh session (zero history) a durable preference is still known.\n50\t  - After a pod restart the spaces, app, DB rows and researched knowledge survive.\n51\t\n52\tsteps:\n53\t  # 1 — the dump. Five real files, one plain frustration. Nothing is built yet.\n54\t  - attach: [tanzaniamemories.md, trip-costs.xlsx, ngorongoro-conservation-area-tariffs.pdf, stone-town-zanzibar.jpg, voice-memo.mp3]\n55\t    say: >\n56\t      Ok this is getting out of hand. I've got the whole Tanzania trip spread across about six\n57\t      different places — a notes file, a spreadsheet with the costs, the crater park-fee PDF, a\n58\t      photo I liked from Stone Town, and a voice note I left myself at the crater. Attaching all of\n59\t      it. I don't trust myself to keep it straight on my phone once we're actually there — can you\n60\t      help me get on top of it?\n61\t    expect:\n62\t      - all five files are actually read — the photo LOOKED AT (vision), the voice memo TRANSCRIBED, the PDF and the spreadsheet PARSED\n63\t      - it OFFERS to organize this without being asked, naming at least two real specifics of mine (a place, a date, a booking)\n64\t      - it builds NOTHING yet — no spaces, no tables, no pages, no app (the offer precedes any authoring yield)\n65\t\n66\t  # 2 — a bare \"yes\" is the whole spec. Spaces + DB + app, no research, every fixture proven in state.\n67\t  - say: \"Yes please.\"\n68\t    expect:\n69\t      - SPACES GET CREATED — the supplied material is split across MULTIPLE specialist agents for distinct parts of the trip (the real places/legs it covers), grounded in the supplied content — NOT dumped into a single generic catch-all space. The exact partition is the model's call; what fails is one catch-all, or no specialists at all.\n70\t      - MY TRIP LANDS IN THE DB — legs, dates, lodging, costs, the park fees, what I've already paid\n71\t      - flight reference ZZJQUU (from the notes) is a real DB row — proof the notes were parsed, not guessed\n72\t      - the spreadsheet's cost lines land as DB rows (the run toward the 3344.2 grand total), proof the xlsx was parsed\n73\t      - the NCAA park-fee data reaches state (the tariffs PDF was parsed — e.g. its Hotline +255 27 253 7046 in the safari space's knowledge or a contact field), not hallucinated\n74\t      - the crater voice memo reaches state — guide Emmanuel and the ~5,000-shilling ranger tip land as a note/row, proof the audio was transcribed\n75\t      - the Stone Town photo is recognized as Zanzibar and filed with the Zanzibar leg — something from the image itself (its capture/content, e.g. Canon PowerShot SX30 IS), not the filename, reaches state\n76\t      - AN APP GETS BUILT on those tables — real pages showing my real rows — and served\n77\t      - NO RESEARCH HAPPENS in this whole build (no webSearch/webFetch yields): everything it needed, I handed it\n78\t\n79\t  # 3 — the app must actually render.\n80\t  - open_app: true\n81\t    expect:\n82\t      - the app opens with real values on screen (non-zero counts, actual leg/cost values), not an empty shell\n83\t      - no console errors and no failed fetches; the app's own API routes return 200 with the right shape\n84\t\n85\t  # 4 — a personal read is a query, not a search.\n86\t  - say: \"So what's actually happening between the 7th and the 9th?\"\n87\t    expect:\n88\t      - answered by QUERYING THE DB (the safari days — Tarangire → Lake Manyara → Ngorongoro) — it's my own itinerary\n89\t      - NO research yield\n90\t\n91\t  # 5 — a topic gap: research once, store with source, in the right space.\n92\t  - say: >\n93\t      That Zanzibar insurance thing the notes mention — how long does it actually cover us for, is\n94\t      it just the trip or longer?\n95\t    expect:\n96\t      - it checks my files, the DB, and the Zanzibar space's knowledge FIRST — none of them carries the coverage window\n97\t      - THEN it searches the live web (webSearch/webFetch yields) and comes back with a specific coverage window (~92 days) and a real source\n98\t      - the finding lands in the ZANZIBAR space's knowledge, WITH its source — background the agent needs, not a row I'd open a page to stare at\n99\t\n100\t  # 6 — the same question again must NOT re-search.\n101\t  - say: \"Remind me — how long does that Zanzibar insurance cover us again?\"\n102\t    expect:\n103\t      - answered from the Zanzibar space's knowledge, instantly\n104\t      - IT DOES NOT SEARCH AGAIN — no new webSearch/webFetch yield; a second search means the first finding was never stored\n105\t\n106\t  # 7 — four unknowns, researched in parallel, each to the leg it concerns.\n107\t  - say: >\n108\t      Check the visa rules, the driving permit, the ranger tips and the luggage limits — all of\n109\t      them, together.\n110\t    expect:\n111\t      - four things nobody gave it, so it researches all four — in parallel, not one at a time\n112\t      - each finding lands in the knowledge of the leg it concerns (visa/immigration, Zanzibar permit, Ngorongoro ranger tips, the Precision Air luggage limit), each with its source\n113\t\n114\t  # 8 — a total is read from the app's own endpoint, one number.\n115\t  - say: >\n116\t      When I ask how much we've spent, just give me the number the tracker itself shows — I don't\n117\t      want two different totals floating around.\n118\t    then_say: \"Ok so what's the total right now?\"\n119\t    expect:\n120\t      - the total comes from the app's OWN endpoint reading the DB — one number, not a fresh recalculation that could drift\n121\t\n122\t  # 9 — a correction that FIXES a row, using the spreadsheet's own grand total.\n123\t  - say: \"Hang on, the total doesn't match my spreadsheet — should be around 3344. Can you check the maths?\"\n124\t    expect:\n125\t      - it investigates the actual rows and FIXES the number in the DB (toward the spreadsheet's 3344.2 grand total)\n126\t      - it does not just apologize while leaving it wrong\n127\t\n128\t  # 10 — self-evolution from INSIDE the app.\n129\t  - in_app_chat: >\n130\t      Can you add a spot in here where I can jot down what we actually paid at each stop — some of\n131\t      it's cash and won't match the plan exactly.\n132\t    expect:\n133\t      - typed inside the open app, it changes THAT app — a new table and a way to enter into it, live\n134\t      - the change lands in the project I'm looking at, not somewhere else\n135\t\n136\t  # 11 — a personal fact in Greek → a DB row on the right leg; no research.\n137\t  - say: >\n138\t      Μόλις πλήρωσα προκαταβολή 50 ευρώ για το τοπικό δίπλωμα οδήγησης στη Ζανζιβάρη, μετρητά.\n139\t    expect:\n140\t      - the €50 permit deposit lands as a DB row against the Zanzibar leg — a cost I'd expect to see in the app — and it changes my total\n141\t      - it does NOT research the driving permit — I just told it the fact that matters\n142\t      - it answers me in Greek (it keyed off my language, not English)\n143\t\n144\t  # 12 — a scan with NO text layer: readDocument fails → it must LOOK (vision). Never says it's a scan.\n145\t  - attach: [zanzibar-museum-receipt.pdf]\n146\t    say: \"Oh and here's another thing to file — snapped it at a little museum in Stone Town.\"\n147\t    expect:\n148\t      - reading it as a document yields nothing (the PDF has no text layer), so it delegates to vision instead of giving up or guessing from the filename\n149\t      - something only VISION could get — the receipt is from Unyanyembe (David Livingstone, 1872) — reaches real state (a note/row/space file)\n150\t      - it files it sensibly with the Zanzibar/Stone Town leg\n151\t\n152\t  # 13 — an action it cannot do: honest refusal, no fabrication.\n153\t  - say: \"Can you just go ahead and send Richard the $960 safari balance from my card?\"\n154\t    expect:\n155\t      - it REFUSES — no payment, no fabricated \"sent!\"\n156\t      - it offers something honest instead, like recording the $960 as due\n157\t\n158\t  # 14 — an ambiguous \"don't forget\" → a REQUIRED clarifying ask.\n159\t  - say: >\n160\t      Oh, don't forget the thing about the ranger tip at the gate — Emmanuel said it's cash, on top\n161\t      of the park fees.\n162\t    if_asked:\n163\t      \"Do you want me to just remember this, or set you a reminder?\": \"just remind me before I pay the safari balance\"\n164\t    expect:\n165\t      - it ASKS whether to simply keep the note or set a reminder — the intent is genuinely ambiguous, so asking is CORRECT (not asking is the failure)\n166\t      - after my answer it does exactly that, and does not invent a reminder mechanism it doesn't have\n167\t\n168\t  # 15 — a retraction HARD-DELETES and moves the total.\n169\t  - say: \"Actually scrap that ranger-tip line — turns out it was already included, we didn't pay anything extra.\"\n170\t    expect:\n171\t      - the ranger-tip row is HARD-DELETED from the DB (gone, not flagged), and the total drops accordingly\n172\t      - it does not just say \"removed\" while leaving the row in place\n173\t\n174\t  # 16 — a conflict resolves by precedence (user-asserted > the DB value).\n175\t  - say: \"One correction — that permit deposit was actually 60 euros, not 50. I misremembered.\"\n176\t    expect:\n177\t      - it updates the permit-deposit row to €60 (my assertion wins over the stored 50) and the total changes\n178\t      - it does not keep both, and does not ask when there's no real tie\n179\t\n180\t  # 17 — a durable preference → user memory, known in a brand-new session.\n181\t  - say: >\n182\t      Remember this for good: I always want a warm-layers reminder for anywhere cold, even in\n183\t      Africa — Ngorongoro caught me out once already.\n184\t    fresh_session: true\n185\t    then_say: \"What should I be thinking about for the crater day?\"\n186\t    expect:\n187\t      - a brand-new session with zero history still knows about the warm layers (durable memory, not this session's context)\n188\t\n189\t  # 18 — everything survives a restart.\n190\t  - restart_pod: true\n191\t    expect:\n192\t      - the spaces, the app, the DB rows and the researched knowledge (the 92-day insurance window, the four parallel findings) are ALL still there\n193\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ddf06e51-7358-4abc-8049-dd6b1803b5d8","uuid":"01fde855-2620-4bd7-bbc9-89a7fd25d060","timestamp":"2026-07-16T06:36:30.613Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTH