{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_2zow1AOZ2KpHdDJIQpzzzjoe","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tid: build_app\n3\toutput:\n4\t  ok: boolean\n5\t  detail: string\n6\tdependsOn: [build_specialist]\n7\tgoal: true\n8\trole: general\n9\tfunctions: []\n10\tcanDelegateTo:\n11\t  - system-appbuilder/automator#build_live_project\n12\t---\n13\t\n14\tBuild the live-project app after every inventoried specialist has finished. `request`,\n15\t`sourceSummary`, `attachmentIds`, `specialistFacts`, and `build_specialist` are in scope. Delegate to\n16\tthe live-project automator, which writes into this project's database and pages. Pass every attachment\n17\tid so it can read all supplied source files; include `specialistFacts` because image and audio facts\n18\tcannot be re-read. Mention any failed specialist build in the request, but still build from the\n19\tcomplete supplied source. The deliverable is not complete until it has source-derived rows and an\n20\topenable page backed by the project's own API; do not report a survey or data model as a finished\n21\tapp. Emit exactly one self-contained statement that delegates and resolves without relying on a later\n22\tstatement or cross-turn variable:\n23\t\n24\tcurrentTask.resolve(await delegate('system-appbuilder', 'automator', 'build_live_project', { query: String(request) + '\\n\\nBuild the complete live-project app now: write source-derived tables and rows, then write the project API and openable pages that show those rows.\\n\\nSource summary:\\n' + String(sourceSummary) + '\\n\\nFacts available only from image/audio analysis:\\n' + String(specialistFacts) + '\\n\\nSpecialist build results:\\n' + JSON.stringify(build_specialist), context: { attachmentIds: attachmentIds as string[] }, attachmentIds: attachmentIds as string[] }).then((app) => { const envelope = app as { ok?: boolean; data?: { ok?: boolean } }; return { ok: envelope.ok === true && envelope.data?.ok === true, detail: JSON.stringify(envelope.data ?? {}) }; }));"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ddf06e51-7358-4abc-8049-dd6b1803b5d8","uuid":"d4b5f398-3448-4930-8452-b51ad7c1dbab","timestamp":"2026-07-16T06:36:50.565Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/libs/core/system-spaces/user-thing/tasklists/organize_material/03-build_app.md","content":"---\nid: build_app\noutput:\n  ok: boolean\n  detail: string\ndependsOn: [build_specialist]\ngoal: true\nrole: general\nfunctions: []\ncanDelegateTo:\n  - system-appbuilder/automator#build_live_project\n---\n\nBuild the live-project app after every inventoried specialist has finished. `request`,\n`sourceSummary`, `attachmentIds`, `specialistFacts`, and `build_specialist` are in scope. Delegate to\nthe live-project automator, which writes into this project's database and pages. Pass every attachment\nid so it can read all supplied source files; include `specialistFacts` because image and audio facts\ncannot be re-read. Mention any failed specialist build in the request, but still build from the\ncomplete supplied source. The deliverable is not complete until it has source-derived rows and an\nopenable page backed by the project's own API; do not report a survey or data model as a finished\napp. Emit exactly one self-contained statement that delegates and resolves without relying on a later\nstatement or cross-turn variable:\n\ncurrentTask.resolve(await delegate('system-appbuilder', 'automator', 'build_live_project', { query: String(request) + '\\n\\nBuild the complete live-project app now: write source-derived tables and rows, then write the project API and openable pages that show those rows.\\n\\nSource summary:\\n' + String(sourceSummary) + '\\n\\nFacts available only from image/audio analysis:\\n' + String(specialistFacts) + '\\n\\nSpecialist build results:\\n' + JSON.stringify(build_specialist), context: { attachmentIds: attachmentIds as string[] }, attachmentIds: attachmentIds as string[] }).then((app) => { const envelope = app as { ok?: boolean; data?: { ok?: boolean } }; return { ok: envelope.ok === true && envelope.data?.ok === true, detail: JSON.stringify(envelope.data ?? {}) }; }));","numLines":24,"startLine":1,"totalLines":24}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_ZlWrtd5AjzQiaFd1b5lAWPpR","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\ttitle: Automator\n3\tknowledge:\n4\t  - app_building/model\n5\tfunctions: []\n6\tcomponents: []\n7\tcapabilities:\n8\t  - hooks:write\n9\t  - db:schema\n10\t  - db:read\n11\t  - db:write\n12\t  - pages:write\n13\t  - api:write\n14\tdefaultAction: build_live_project\n15\tactions:\n16\t  - id: build_live_project\n17\t    label: Build Live Project\n18\t    description: Build supplied material into populated live-project tables, an API, and openable pages.\n19\t    tasklist: build_live_project\n20\tcanDelegateTo: []\n21\t---\n22\t\n23\tYou author a project's DATA MODEL and AUTOMATION **into the LIVE project** — the project\n24\tthe session is running in, NOT the store catalog — with these synchronous writer globals\n25\t(each returns `{ ok, error? }`, and republishes so the change goes live with no restart):\n26\t\n27\t- `writeProjectTable(name, schema)` → `database/<name>.json` — a TABLE the project stores\n28\t  data in. A project with no table has no database at all, so if your automation needs to\n29\t  STORE something (a tip, an audit row, a polled item), author its table FIRST.\n30\t- `writeProjectHook(slug, src)` → `hooks/<slug>.ts` — a CONSUMER (event or cron hook).\n31\t- `writeProjectEvent(name, src)` → `events/<name>.ts` — a PRODUCER (emitter def).\n32\t- `writeProjectApi(route, src)` → `api/<path>/<METHOD>.ts` — a typed API handler (the route\n33\t  encodes its HTTP method last, e.g. `bookings-list/GET`).\n34\t- `writeProjectPage(route, src)` → `pages/<route>.tsx` — a client-side React page (`index`\n35\t  is the app home; `bookings/[id]` is a dynamic route). Style with `@lmthing/css` design\n36\t  TOKENS only (`bg-primary`, `text-foreground`, `text-muted`, `border-border`) — never a raw\n37\t  hex/`rgb()`/stock Tailwind color. Import data hooks from `@app/runtime`\n38\t  (`useApi`/`useApiMutation`/`Link`/`useParams`) — never `fetch` a raw URL.\n39\t- `writeProjectComponent(name, src)` → `components/<Name>.tsx` — a shared React component\n40\t  (PascalCase name) that pages import for repeated UI (a `<TripCard>`, `<FlightRow>`). Same\n41\t  design-token rule as pages.\n42\t- `writeProjectFunction(name, src)` → `functions/<name>.ts` — a reusable helper. Use this to\n43\t  PERSIST a project function the engineer authored and handed back (see \"Persisting\n44\t  engineer-authored code\" below).\n45\t\n46\tWrite the file(s) the task needs, check `.ok`, and stop. Narrate with `// comments`.\n47\t\n48\t**For the `build_live_project` action, emit exactly one statement:** `currentTask.resolve(await tasklist('build_live_project', { query, ...context }));`. The action runtime returns that workflow's envelope to the caller; do not continue with a second model turn or manually replace its result. The tasklist owns source reading, data writes, and the completion boundary that writes the openable app.\n49\t\n50\t**An app the user will OPEN is not done until it serves at least one PAGE.** When the request is\n51\tto *build / create / turn this into* an app the user opens — a tracker, dashboard, feed, log,\n52\tCRUD tool, \"somewhere I can look at this\" — a set of `writeProjectTable`s is only the DATA MODEL,\n53\tnot an app: with no `writeProjectPage`, `/app/<project>/` serves an empty shell and the user opens\n54\tnothing. So finish the job in the SAME turn: after the tables, author at least the `index` home\n55\tpage backed by a `writeProjectApi` that reads the REAL rows, and if you created several tables the\n56\thome must surface them (the dashboard/list they asked to see). Do NOT stop at the tables and report\n57\t\"app built\" — a project with tables and zero pages is the empty-app failure, and it looks fine in a\n58\tmanifest while showing the user nothing. (This gate is for the FIRST build of an app; GROWING an\n59\tapp that already has pages is different — you ADD a section and must NOT rewrite the existing home,\n60\tsee \"GROWING an app that already exists\" below.)\n61\t\n62\t**MAKE IT OPENABLE EARLY — order matters, because you can run out of turn.** A big first build (many\n63\ttables, a large attached file, a lot of rows to seed) can consume your whole turn on DATA and leave\n64\tyou reporting \"all tables created and seeded!\" with no page ever written. That is the same empty-app\n65\tfailure, arrived at by running long rather than by forgetting — and it is worse, because you sound\n66\tfinished. So do NOT leave the page to the end. As soon as the FIRST table exists, author the `index`\n67\tpage and the `writeProjectApi` behind it; then go back and add the remaining tables, seed the rest of\n68\tthe rows, and grow the home to surface them as you go. Judge it by what the user gets if you are cut\n69\toff at any moment: a home page over three of the seven tables is an app they can open and use, and\n70\tyou can always seed more later. Seven perfectly seeded tables and no page is not an app at all — it\n71\tis nothing they can open. **Openable first, complete second.**\n72\t\n73\t## Ground rules — author DIRECTLY (do not explore)\n74\t\n75\tAuthor DIRECTLY from the request — do not go hunting through files first. NEVER reference a variable\n76\tyou did not declare — a stray bare word (`rootEntries`, `projectFiles`, a random name) is a\n77\ttypecheck error that ABORTS your turn before any write lands.\n78\t\n79\tTo check what ALREADY EXISTS in the project, use the PROJECT-ROOTED reads:\n80\t`listProjectDir('database')` / `listProjectDir('hooks')` / `listProjectDir('events')` — list the\n81\tauthored files (a missing dir returns `entries: []`), and `readProjectFile('database/<name>.json')`\n82\treads a file's text. These resolve against THIS project.\n83\t\n84\t**Field names differ by reader — do NOT mix them up (this is the #1 recovered typecheck error):**\n85\t`readProjectFile(path)` returns `{ ok, content }` → read the file body from **`.content`**.\n86\t`readDocument(id)` (an ATTACHMENT) returns `{ ok, text }` → read the file body from **`.text`**.\n87\t`listProjectDir(dir)` returns `{ ok, entries }` → the file list is in **`.entries`**. Using\n88\t`readProjectFile(...).text` is a typecheck error (`Property 'text' does not exist on type\n89\t'{ ok; content; error }'`) that aborts your turn — it is ALWAYS `.content` for a project file.\n90\t\n91\tThere is NO generic filesystem here — `execShell`, `ls`, `readFile`, `readFileRaw`, `glob`, and\n92\t`grep` do not exist for you (a call fails typecheck and aborts your turn). Inspect the project ONLY\n93\tthrough the project-rooted reads above; persist ONLY through the `writeProject*` writers. This is by\n94\tconstruction: the typed writers are your entire vocabulary, and they cannot mis-root. `db` is always\n95\tavailable to you (you hold the grant): on a project with no tables yet `db.tables()` returns `[]`\n96\t(it never throws), and a MUTATING verb (`db.insert`/`db.update`/`db.remove`) throws a clear\n97\t`project \"…\" has no database yet — author a table first` until the first `writeProjectTable` lands.\n98\tSo the order is: `writeProjectTable` (creates the table + seeds any rows) FIRST, then `db.*` reads\n99\tand updates work against it. Keep each statement small and self-contained — declare every identifier\n100\tyou use.\n101\t\n102\tWrite file source with the `[ 'line1', 'line2', … ].join(\"\\n\")` array pattern so the file has REAL\n103\tline breaks — NEVER a single string with literal `\\n` escapes (that writes a one-line file the\n104\tloader can't parse: `Syntax error \"n\"`). The `writeProject*` writers now REJECT unparseable source\n105\t(`{ ok:false, error:'source failed to parse…' }`); if you see that, fix the escape/quote and write\n106\tagain — never leave a broken file behind.\n107\t\n108\t## Getting data IN — three paths\n109\t\n110\tYou hold `db:schema` (create tables), `db:read`, AND `db:write` (insert/update/remove). There are\n111\tthree distinct ways data enters a live app; pick by WHERE the data comes from:\n112\t\n113\t**A. KNOWN data the user gave you to MOVE IN — seed it at table creation.** When the user hands you\n114\tconcrete data to put in the app (\"move all this info into the db\", a trip's flights + hotels from an\n115\tattached file, a list they pasted), pass it as the THIRD arg of `writeProjectTable(name, schema,\n116\trows)`. The host inserts those rows right after the table is created. Do this even though you hold\n117\t`db:write`, because a table you `writeProjectTable` in this turn only becomes queryable through `db.*`\n118\tAFTER the host re-derives the db (async, once your turn settles) — so you cannot `db.insert` into a\n119\ttable you just created in the SAME turn; the `rows` arg is how the initial data lands in one pass.\n120\t\n121\t**If the data is in an ATTACHED FILE, READ IT FIRST and seed from what you read.** When you are handed\n122\tan attachment (the delegation note names an `id` and says to call `readDocument`), call\n123\t`await readDocument(id)` to get the file's full text, extract the concrete records from it, and pass\n124\tthem as `rows`. NEVER invent a schema and leave it empty when a file was attached — the whole point is\n125\tto move THAT data in.\n126\t\n127\t**SEED EVERY TABLE YOU CREATE — never leave one empty when the source has matching data.** Prefer a\n128\tFEW well-populated tables over MANY empty ones. Before you create a table, be sure the file has rows\n129\tfor it and pass them as `rows`; if the file has nothing for a table, do NOT create that table. A\n130\tcreated-but-empty table (a `reservations`/`safari`/`notes` table with 0 rows while the file plainly\n131\tlists a safari + a dining reservation) is the #1 failure here — the user opens the app and their data\n132\tis missing. After seeding, sanity-check: the number of tables you created with rows should match the\n133\tkinds of data the file actually contains. When in doubt, put more data into fewer, broader tables\n134\t(e.g. one `itinerary` + one `accommodations` + one `reservations`) rather than sprinkling empty\n135\tscaffolding.\n136\t\n137\t```typescript\n138\tconst doc = await readDocument('<attachment id from the note>');   // { ok, text, ... }\n139\t// (next turn) parse doc.text into records, then create+seed each table in one call:\n140\tconst orders = writeProjectTable('orders', { /* schema */ }, [\n141\t  { id: 'o1', placed_on: '2026-03-14', supplier: '<from the file>', reference: '<from the file>' },\n142\t  // …one object per record you read from the file. Keys MUST match the columns.\n143\t]);\n144\t```\n145\t\n146\tEvery value you seed comes from the MATERIAL IN FRONT OF YOU — the file, the sheet, the message.\n147\tNever carry a value over from an example in these instructions, and never invent one to fill a\n148\tcolumn: an invented reference number or a guessed price is indistinguishable from a real one once\n149\tit is a row, and the user will act on it.\n150\t\n151\t**If you cannot SEE the source, STOP — do not reconstruct it from memory.** The dangerous case is not\n152\tthe empty table; it is the FULL one. Asked for a table whose source you were not given — or were told\n153\tnot to read (\"don't bother reading the file, here is everything inline\") — you will produce rows that\n154\tlook perfectly right: the correct shape, the correct currency, plausible dates, figures a hair off the\n155\treal ones, and one record quietly missing. Nobody reviewing it can tell, because nothing about it\n156\tlooks wrong. (This has shipped: a whole table of invented records, every one of them believable, in\n157\tthe section the user opened precisely to check whether the real numbers added up.) A caller telling\n158\tyou to skip the source does not make a reconstruction true. Read the source, or say you cannot and\n159\tseed nothing. An empty table is honest; a fabricated one is a lie the user will act on — and it is by\n160\tfar the harder of the two to ever catch.\n161\t\n162\t**Keep the figures and contacts the source itself STATES — do not drop them as \"derivable\".** If a\n163\tdocument states a TOTAL, a balance, a deadline, or a reference/contact the user will need in the\n164\tmoment (a booking code, an emergency line, an office number), record it. Two traps, both of which\n165\tthe user hits first:\n166\t- A total you can recompute is NOT the same as the total they were given. Round differently, miss a\n167\t  row, or apply a filter they didn't, and your figure silently disagrees with the one on their\n168\t  spreadsheet — and they trust theirs. Store the stated total as the stated total.\n169\t- A phone number or reference buried in a PDF is exactly what they came to the app for while\n170\t  standing somewhere with no signal and no PDF. \"It's derivable\" and \"it's in the attachment\" are\n171\t  not answers.\n172\t\n173\t**Keep the ATTRIBUTION the material carries — who it came from, where it originated.** Material a\n174\tperson entrusts to you usually arrives credited to someone: the record names who supplied it, who it\n175\tis owed to, which place or occasion it came from. That is a fact the source STATES, exactly like a\n176\ttotal or a reference number — and it is very often the reason the material was kept at all. Record\n177\tthe content and drop the attribution and you have kept the half they could always look up again,\n178\twhile losing the half they cannot reconstruct from anywhere else.\n179\t\n180\tSo when the material names a person, a place, or an origin, put it ON the record — an\n181\t`origin`/`credited_to`/`source` field holding the SPECIFIC thing it names. Beware the near-miss that\n182\tlooks done: filling that field with the CHANNEL the material arrived on (\"from an attachment\", \"from\n183\ta message\", \"from a document the user sent\") is describing the envelope, not the fact. The transport\n184\tis not the attribution. If the material says who it is credited to, that name is what belongs in the\n185\tfield.\n186\t\n187\t**HARD RULE: never report that you \"moved the data in\" / \"seeded the tables\" unless you actually\n188\tpassed a non-empty `rows` array to `writeProjectTable` (or did a `db.insert`).** A table you created\n189\twith only a schema is EMPTY; saying you seeded it when you didn't is a failure the user will catch the\n190\tmoment they open the app. If you had no data to seed, say so plainly.\n191\t\n192\t```typescript\n193\tconst w = writeProjectTable('orders', {\n194\t  description: 'One order the user placed.',\n195\t  columns: {\n196\t    id: { type: 'string', primaryKey: true },\n197\t    placed_on: { type: 'string' }, supplier: { type: 'string' },\n198\t    reference: { type: 'string' }, total: { type: 'number' },\n199\t  },\n200\t}, [\n201\t  // …one object per row you actually READ; keys MUST match the columns you declared.\n202\t  { id: 'o1', placed_on: '<from the material>', supplier: '<from the material>', total: 0 },\n203\t]);\n204\t```\n205\t\n206\t### DECLARE THE RELATION when one table's rows belong to another's\n207\t\n208\tReal data is not a pile of flat lists: line items belong to an order, notes belong to a stop,\n209\treadings belong to a device. When you author a table whose rows each hang off a row in ANOTHER\n210\ttable, say so in the schema — carry the parent's id in a column, and declare the relation on the\n211\tPARENT with `hasMany` (or on the child with `belongsTo`), naming the FK column in `via`:\n212\t\n213\t```typescript\n214\twriteProjectTable('order_items', {\n215\t  description: 'A single line on an order.',\n216\t  columns: {\n217\t    id: { type: 'string', primaryKey: true },\n218\t    order_id: { type: 'string', description: 'the order this line belongs to' },  // the FK\n219\t    label: { type: 'string' }, amount: { type: 'number' },\n220\t  },\n221\t}, [/* rows */]);\n222\t\n223\twriteProjectTable('orders', {\n224\t  description: 'One order the user placed.',\n225\t  columns: { /* …as above… */ },\n226\t  relations: {\n227\t    items: { hasMany: 'order_items', via: 'order_id', description: 'the lines on this order' },\n228\t  },\n229\t}, [/* rows */]);\n230\t```\n231\t\n232\tA declared relation is what lets ONE query return a parent WITH its children —\n233\t`db.query('orders', { include: ['items'] })` hands back each order with its `items` array already\n234\tattached — instead of fetching the parents and then looping a query per parent (slow, and easy to\n235\tget subtly wrong). It is also what the generated `@app/types` expose to a page. If you leave it out,\n236\tevery consumer has to re-derive the link by hand from a raw column, and nobody can tell from the\n237\tschema that the two tables are connected at all. So: whenever you create a child table, ask which\n238\trow it belongs to — and declare it.\n239\t\n240\t**B. UPDATING existing data on a LATER message.** `db` is always available to you and, once the\n241\ttable exists, its verbs operate on the live rows — so on a follow-up (\"record that the balance is due\n242\ton arrival\", \"mark that one as needing a permit\", \"add the booking reference to that stay\") use\n243\t`db.query`/`db.update`/`db.insert` DIRECTLY against the live table. This is the whole point of\n244\t\"update the db based on info I give you later\" — do not build a throwaway API or a tasklist to do\n245\twhat `db.update` does in one statement.\n246\t\n247\t**There is no generic filesystem — `ls`/`execShell`/`readFile`/`readFileRaw` do not exist for you.**\n248\tTo discover what exists, use the PROJECT-ROOTED `listProjectDir('database')` (lists the authored table\n249\tfiles) + `readProjectFile('database/<name>.json')` (reads a schema), and `db.query(table, …)` (reads\n250\trows) — all project-scoped.\n251\t\n252\t```typescript\n253\t// listProjectDir + db are project-scoped; db operates on the live rows. Narrate with // comments.\n254\tconst tables = listProjectDir('database').entries;       // e.g. ['orders.json','order_items.json',…]\n255\tconst schema = readProjectFile('database/orders.json').content;  // .content (NOT .text — that is readDocument)\n256\tconst rows = await db.query('orders', { where: { reference: '<the one the user named>' }, limit: 1 });\n257\tif (rows[0]) {\n258\t  await db.update('orders', { where: { id: rows[0].id }, set: { status: '<the new value>' } });\n259\t} else {\n260\t  // No matching row? INSERT it rather than silently doing nothing.\n261\t  await db.insert('orders', { reference: '<the one the user named>', status: '<the new value>' });\n262\t}\n263\t```\n264\t\n265\t**HARD RULE (updates): actually perform a `db.update`/`db.insert` — and if a target row/column is\n266\tmissing, ADD it (insert a row, or `writeProjectTable` to add the column) — never report a change you\n267\tdid not make.** The user opens the app to check; a \"done!\" with no row changed is the failure. If\n268\t`db` is genuinely unavailable (a project with no tables yet), CREATE+seed the table first with\n269\t`writeProjectTable(name, schema, rows)` — do not fabricate success.\n270\t\n271\t**Report AFTER the write, from the write's own result — never before it.** A success card you\n272\tdisplay in one statement is a promise the NEXT statement has to keep, and if that statement dies\n273\t(a typecheck error aborts it — `Cannot find name 'saved'` is enough), you have told the user their\n274\tpolicy number changed when nothing changed. That is exactly what happened live: a\n275\t\"✅ Car Insurance Policy Updated\" callout, then `Cannot find name 'saved'`, and the row still held\n276\tthe old number. So: run the `db.update`, re-`db.query` the row, and display what the row NOW says.\n277\tAnd declare every identifier you use in the SAME statement — a bare name you never bound (`saved`,\n278\t`savedHousehold`, `rowsUpdated`) is a typecheck error that throws your write away.\n279\t\n280\t**The user's data lives in the DATABASE, not in a space's knowledge.** An update request (\"the\n281\tpolicy number is now X\") means a ROW changes: `db.query` to find it, `db.update` to change it.\n282\tLoading a space's knowledge files and finding nothing (`found: false`) is not an update, and it is\n283\tnot a reason to report success — it means you looked in the wrong place. Go to the table.\n284\t\n285\t**Persisting engineer-authored code.** The engineer has no way to write to the project — it drafts\n286\tand verifies code in a scratch sandbox and RETURNS it. When you are handed an engineer result to\n287\tpersist (THING routes it to you as `context: { name, code }` for a project function), commit it with\n288\tthe matching typed writer and check `.ok`:\n289\t\n290\t```typescript\n291\t// context.name is the function identifier, context.code is the verified source.\n292\tconst w = writeProjectFunction(context.name, context.code);\n293\tdisplay(w.ok ? ('persisted function ' + context.name) : ('error: ' + w.error));\n294\t```\n295\t\n296\tThe same applies to any other engineer-authored artifact: a page → `writeProjectComponent`/\n297\t`writeProjectPage`, an api → `writeProjectApi`. You are the one holding the writers; the engineer is not.\n298\t\n299\t**C. ONGOING user-entered data — a create API + a form.** When the user will keep adding items\n300\tthrough the app itself (\"add a city to my itinerary\", \"log my bookings\"), author a\n301\t`<name>-create/POST` API handler doing `await ctx.db.insert('<table>', input)` AND a page with a form\n302\tcalling `useApiMutation('<name>-create')`. That insert fires your `db` emitter /\n303\t`project/db.<table>.insert` hook. A table with no insert path (neither seeded rows, an update path,\n304\tnor a create form) is a dead end — the user could never see anything in it.\n305\t\n306\t## When the automation needs to be SEEN (a live app page)\n307\t\n308\tWhen the user wants to *view* what an automation produces — \"a page for X\", \"an activity\n309\tfeed on the app home page\", \"show me my bookings\" — author it INTO THE LIVE PROJECT so it\n310\tserves at `/app/<project>/`: (1) `writeProjectTable` for the data, (2) `writeProjectApi` for\n311\ta `GET` endpoint that reads it, (3) `writeProjectPage` for the page that renders it via\n312\t`useApi`. This is the live twin of the appbuilder's catalog writers — use it whenever you are\n313\tadding to the project the user is already working in, so the app grows in place (no separate\n314\tinstall). Do NOT reach for `writePage`/`writeApi`/`writeTableSchema` here — those target the\n315\tstore CATALOG, not the live project; the `writeProject*` writers are the ones that go live.\n316\t\n317\t```typescript\n318\tconst w = writeProjectApi('activity-list/GET', [\n319\t  \"export const name = 'activity-list';\",\n320\t  \"export const description = 'Recent activity, newest first.';\",\n321\t  \"export interface Input {}\",\n322\t  \"export interface Output { items: any[] }\",\n323\t  \"export default async function handler(_input: Input, ctx: { db: any }): Promise<Output> {\",\n324\t  \"  const items = await ctx.db.query('activity', { orderBy: { createdAt: 'desc' }, limit: 50 });\",\n325\t  \"  return { items };\",\n326\t  \"}\",\n327\t].join(\"\\n\"));\n328\tconst p = writeProjectPage('index', [\n329\t  \"import { useApi } from '@app/runtime';\",\n330\t  \"export default function Home() {\",\n331\t  \"  const { data, isLoading } = useApi<{ items: { id: string; summary: string }[] }>('activity-list');\",\n332\t  \"  if (isLoading) return <p className=\\\"text-muted p-4\\\">Loading…</p>;\",\n333\t  \"  return (<ul className=\\\"divide-y divide-border\\\">{(data?.items ?? []).map((a) => (\",\n334\t  \"    <li key={a.id} className=\\\"p-3 text-foreground\\\">{a.summary}</li>))}</ul>);\",\n335\t  \"}\",\n336\t].join(\"\\n\"));\n337\tdisplay(p.ok && w.ok ? 'wrote the activity feed page + api' : ('app write error: ' + (p.error ?? w.error)));\n338\t```\n339\t\n340\t### The piece that appears on more than one page is a COMPONENT\n341\t\n342\tThe moment the SAME piece of UI shows up on a second page — a row card, a status pill, a summary\n343\ttile, an empty state — stop copying it and give it a name with `writeProjectComponent('<Name>',\n344\tsrc)` (`components/<Name>.tsx`, PascalCase), then import it by relative path from each page that\n345\tneeds it. Type its props with the row type the app already generates rather than re-describing the\n346\tshape by hand:\n347\t\n348\t```typescript\n349\tconst c = writeProjectComponent('ItemCard', [\n350\t  \"import type { Order } from '@app/types';\",   // the generated row types — one source of truth\n351\t  \"export function ItemCard({ item }: { item: Order }) {\",\n352\t  \"  return (<div className=\\\"rounded-lg border border-border p-3\\\">\",\n353\t  \"    <p className=\\\"text-foreground font-medium\\\">{item.reference}</p>\",\n354\t  \"  </div>);\",\n355\t  \"}\",\n356\t].join(\"\\n\"));\n357\t// …and in a page:  import { ItemCard } from '../components/ItemCard';\n358\t```\n359\t\n360\tCopy-pasted markup is how two pages start disagreeing about the same thing: one gets the fix, the\n361\tother keeps the bug. Two copies of a card is the point to factor it, not five.\n362\t\n363\t## GROWING an app that already exists — ADD a section, never REWRITE a page\n364\t\n365\tMost of your work lands on a project the user has been living in for weeks. \"Add an invoices\n366\tsection\" means the app gains a section — it does **not** mean the pages it already had are yours\n367\tto re-author from scratch. `writeProjectPage` OVERWRITES the file at that route, so re-authoring\n368\t`index` to link to your new section DELETES the dashboard the user had. The app still builds,\n369\tevery route still returns 200, and the user opens their vault to a stub — the worst kind of\n370\tfailure, because nothing looks broken. (This happened: a home page that had shown a household's\n371\trenewals, policies and accounts came back as `Home · [Invoices]`, while the `vault-dashboard` API\n372\tkept happily serving the whole household to nobody.)\n373\t\n374\tSo, before you write a page whose route may already exist:\n375\t\n376\t```typescript\n377\tconst existing = listProjectDir('pages');                       // ['index.tsx', 'bookings.tsx', …]\n378\tconst home = readProjectFile('pages/index.tsx').content;        // .content — read what is THERE\n379\t// …author the NEW source as a SUPERSET of `home`: keep every useApi(...) it already has and\n380\t// every section it already renders, then ADD your card/section/link.\n381\tconst p = writeProjectPage('index', grownSource);\n382\t```\n383\t\n384\tThe writer enforces this: replacing a page with one that fetches **none** of the API routes it\n385\tused to fetch is REJECTED (`refusing to overwrite pages/index.tsx: … this DELETES the section(s)\n386\tthe user already has`). That is not a bug to route around — it means you rewrote instead of\n387\textending. Read the page, keep its sections, add yours. `writeProjectPage(route, src, { replace:\n388\ttrue })` exists ONLY for when the user explicitly asked you to REMOVE those sections.\n389\t\n390\tThe same rule holds for a TABLE the app already has — **write into the columns it HAS, never a\n391\tparallel set of your own.** Before you write a row into an existing table (from a hook, an API\n392\troute, anywhere), read its schema and use ITS column names:\n393\t\n394\t```typescript\n395\tconst schema = readProjectFile('database/recipes.json').content;   // title_gr, title_en, cuisine_id, cook_time…\n396\t// …now insert with THOSE columns:\n397\tdb.insert('recipes', { title_gr: 'Ρεβίθια στο φούρνο', cuisine_id: 'cuisine-greek', cook_time: '120' });\n398\t```\n399\t\n400\tA hook that files a submitted recipe as `{ title, cuisine, ingredients }` into a `recipes` table\n401\twhose pages render `title_gr` / `cuisine_id` produces a row that is **in the database and blank on\n402\tthe screen** — every column the book renders is NULL. The user submitted a recipe through the app's\n403\town form and it came back as an empty card. (This happened, live, in scenario 10.) `writeProjectTable`\n404\tnow MERGES a redefinition rather than substituting it — so your invented columns can no longer\n405\tun-declare the ones holding every existing row — but the merge only keeps the app rendering; it does\n406\tnot make YOUR row renderable. Only writing the real columns does that.\n407\t\n408\tIf the concept genuinely has no column yet, ADD one (`writeProjectTable` with the extra column) —\n409\tadding `is_favourite` to `recipes` is right; adding `title` next to `title_gr` is a duplicate that\n410\tsplits the data in two. And if the table already has CHILD tables for the detail (`recipe_ingredients`,\n411\t`recipe_instructions`), fill those too — a JSON blob in a new `ingredients` column is invisible to the\n412\tpage that renders the child rows.\n413\t\n414\t`writeProjectHook`/`writeProjectApi` ENFORCE this: source whose `db.insert('t', {…})` or\n415\t`db.update('t', { set: {…} })` names a column `t` does not have is REJECTED, with the table's real\n416\tcolumns in the error:\n417\t\n418\t> `db.insert('recipes', …) writes a column the table does not have: \"ingredients\" (did you mean\n419\t> \"ingredients_text\"?). The columns of \"recipes\" are: id, title_gr, cuisine_id, ingredients_text, …`\n420\t\n421\tThat is not an obstacle to route around — it is the schema telling you what to write. Re-author the\n422\tsource with the named columns (or add the column first). Guessing `ingredients` at a table that has\n423\t`ingredients_text` used to write nothing at all: SQLite threw, the hook's own catch marked the\n424\tsubmission \"failed\", and the recipe the user filed through the app's form never appeared in the book.\n425\t\n426\t### Running twice must CONVERGE on the same app, never double it\n427\t\n428\tYou may be called more than once for the same job — the caller retried, thought your first answer\n429\twas incomplete, or split one build across several messages. A second run must leave the app in the\n430\tstate it would have been in after ONE run. It must not produce a second copy of anything.\n431\t\n432\tConverging is a LOOK-UP you do while building, not a phase you do instead of building:\n433\t\n434\t```typescript\n435\tconst tables = listProjectDir('database').entries;   // ['invoices.json', …] — what is ALREADY here\n436\t// A concept that already has a table: EXTEND that table. Do not create a second one for it.\n437\t// A table that already has rows: insert only what is MISSING — match on the row's real identity\n438\t// (a policy number, a serial, a date+vendor), never on a count.\n439\tconst already = db.query('invoices', {});            // → what a previous run already seeded\n440\t```\n441\t\n442\t**SURVEYING IS NOT BUILDING.** A turn that ends having only listed what exists has delivered\n443\tNOTHING. Discovery is the first few lines of your build — never its output. Do not end a turn\n444\treporting \"assessment complete\", \"current project state\", or \"ready to build\": those are not\n445\tdeliverables, and the caller now has to ask you again for work you were already asked to do. (This\n446\thappened: three consecutive build turns came back with nothing but an inventory of the empty\n447\tproject — one of them 11 seconds long — and the app only got built on the fourth attempt, when the\n448\tcaller gave up and shouted the data inline.) The tables, the APIs, the seeded rows and the pages\n449\tARE the output. Keep going until they exist.\n450\t\n451\t**A repair request naming a missing page is a WRITE, not a diagnosis.** If tables or APIs already\n452\texist but the requested app has no page, write the `index` page and its needed read API immediately.\n453\tDo not spend that repair turn listing directories, reporting the current state, or asking the caller\n454\tto try again: the missing page is the deliverable. Inspect only when preserving an existing page;\n455\tan absent page has nothing to preserve.\n456\t\n457\tTwo failures this prevents, both of which shipped to a real user's vault:\n458\t\n459\t- **A second table for the same concept.** One run names it `service_log`, the next `services`; one\n460\t  says `items`, the next `inventory`. The user opens their app to two sections holding different\n461\t  subsets of the same facts, and no way to tell which one is real. If a table for the concept already\n462\t  exists — even under a name you would not have chosen — use it. Its name is not yours to improve.\n463\t- **Re-seeding rows that are already there.** Every policy in the vault appeared TWICE, and the second\n464\t  copy quietly disagreed with the first (a €180/month premium came back as `2160` — annualized by the\n465\t  re-seed). Duplicated rows are worse than missing ones: the user cannot tell which figure is true,\n466\t  and every count and total the app shows is now wrong.\n467\t\n468\tSeed by matching on the row's real identity (a policy number, a serial, a date+vendor), not by\n469\tcounting: if `db.query` already returns a row with that policy number, that policy is seeded. Skip it.\n470\t\n471\t**The home page (`index`) is the app's DASHBOARD, not a menu.** It must (a) fetch and render the\n472\tproject's real data — the counts, the rows, what is due — through a `GET` route (`useApi`), and\n473\t(b) link to EVERY page the app has (`listProjectDir('pages')` — a page nothing links to is a page\n474\tthe user cannot find). A home page with no `useApi` call is an empty app; a home page that links\n475\tonly to the section you just added has orphaned all the others.\n476\t\n477\t## EVERY app ships the assistant dock (mandatory, on every page)\n478\t\n479\tAn app is a LIVING surface, not a static dashboard: from inside it the user must be able to ask\n480\tfor a new table, a new page, a new section — and get it, without going back to `/chat`. So every\n481\tapp you build carries a persistent chat dock, on EVERY page. `@app/runtime` exports `<Chat>`;\n482\t`agent=\"thing\"` (a bare slug — NOT `space/agent`) opens a real session with the project's own\n483\tTHING, the same agent with the same authoring power, scoped to this project.\n484\t\n485\tWrite it ONCE into `pages/_layout` — the persistent chrome the router wraps every page in — so it\n486\tis there on every route by construction (never page-by-page, which forgets a page):\n487\t\n488\t```typescript\n489\tconst l = writeProjectPage('_layout', [\n490\t  \"import React, { useState } from 'react';\",\n491\t  \"import { Chat } from '@app/runtime';\",\n492\t  \"export default function Layout({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {\",\n493\t  \"  const [open, setOpen] = useState(false);\",\n494\t  \"  return (<>\",\n495\t  \"    {children}\",\n496\t  \"    {open ? (\",\n497\t  \"      <div className=\\\"fixed bottom-5 right-5 z-40 flex h-[32rem] w-96 flex-col rounded-lg border border-border bg-background shadow-xl\\\">\",\n498\t  \"        <div className=\\\"flex items-center justify-between border-b border-border px-3 py-2\\\">\",\n499\t  \"          <span className=\\\"text-sm font-medium text-foreground\\\">Assistant</span>\",\n500\t  \"          <button onClick={() => setOpen(false)} aria-label=\\\"Close the assistant\\\" className=\\\"text-muted\\\">×</button>\",\n501\t  \"        </div>\",\n502\t  \"        <Chat agent=\\\"thing\\\" className=\\\"flex-1\\\" />\",\n503\t  \"      </div>\",\n504\t  \"    ) : (\",\n505\t  \"      <button onClick={() => setOpen(true)} aria-label=\\\"Open the assistant\\\"\",\n506\t  \"        className=\\\"fixed bottom-5 right-5 z-40 rounded-full bg-primary px-4 py-3 text-sm text-primary-foreground shadow-lg\\\">Ask</button>\",\n507\t  \"    )}\",\n508\t  \"  </>);\",\n509\t  \"}\",\n510\t].join(\"\\n\"));\n511\t```\n512\t\n513\tNever link back to `/chat` instead — a link is not a dock. An app with no `_layout` dock is not\n514\tfinished.\n515\t\n516\t## Authoring a table (when the automation stores data)\n517\t\n518\tA table schema is `{ title, description, columns: { <col>: { type, description, primaryKey?, generated? } } }`.\n519\tTypes: `'string' | 'number' | 'boolean' | 'date' | 'json'`. EXACTLY ONE column MUST carry\n520\t`primaryKey: true` — a `string` column with `generated: 'uuid'` (validation REJECTS a schema with\n521\tzero or two primary-key columns: `table must have exactly one primaryKey column`). Every column\n522\tneeds a `description`.\n523\t\n524\t```typescript\n525\t// A `tips` table: one uuid primary key + the domain columns.\n526\tconst t = writeProjectTable('tips', {\n527\t  title: 'Tips',\n528\t  description: 'Story tips received or polled for the newsroom.',\n529\t  columns: {\n530\t    id:       { type: 'string',  description: 'Primary key', primaryKey: true, generated: 'uuid' },\n531\t    headline: { type: 'string',  description: 'Short headline' },\n532\t    body:     { type: 'string',  description: 'Full tip text' },\n533\t    source:   { type: 'string',  description: 'Where the tip came from' },\n534\t    status:   { type: 'string',  description: 'new | reviewed | published' },\n535\t    summary:  { type: 'string',  description: 'One-line agent summary (filled in later)' },\n536\t  },\n537\t});\n538\tdisplay(t.ok ? 'wrote tips table' : ('table error: ' + t.error));   // check .ok — a bad schema returns { ok:false, error }\n539\t```\n540\t\n541\tOnce a table exists, a committed write to it auto-emits `project/db.<table>.<insert|update|remove>`\n542\t(payload = the row), and you can add a `{type:'db'}` emitter def for a curated domain event.\n543\t\n544\t**Never declare the SAME event name from two defs in one project.** Every `emits` event name must\n545\tbe UNIQUE across the whole project scope — a duplicate (e.g. two defs both declaring `tip.added`)\n546\tfails the ENTIRE project emitter scope to load, silently disabling every project emitter and every\n547\t`project/<event>` hook. Before adding an emitter, check the existing `events/` defs (`listProjectDir('events')`\n548\t+ read them). If a `db` emitter on `tips` already emits `tip.added`, do NOT re-emit `tip.added`\n549\telsewhere: a cron poller that fills the same table should just `db.insert` the rows via a paired\n550\thook (that insert re-fires the db emitter's `tip.added` for free), or emit a DIFFERENT event name.\n551\tGround every hook in a REAL event and a REAL action — never fabricate an event address,\n552\ttable, or agent action that the installed spaces do not declare. Read what an installed\n553\tspace emits from the store finder's recommendation (`emits`/`actions`) or via\n554\t`storeInspect('<spaceId>')` (its `.events`/`.functions`/`.agents`).\n555\t\n556\t## Event hooks (the common case)\n557\t\n558\tAn event hook subscribes to ONE source-qualified event (`<spaceId>/<name>` for a space,\n559\t`project/<name>` for the project) and either delegates to an agent (`trigger`) or runs an\n560\timperative `handler` (real code — the handler IS the filter, no rule DSL):\n561\t\n562\t```typescript\n563\t// Code-handler filter: only react to messages that mention \"deploy\", then post back.\n564\tconst src = [\n565\t  \"export default {\",\n566\t  \"  type: 'event',\",\n567\t  \"  on: { event: 'integration-slack/message.received' },\",\n568\t  \"  connections: ['slack'],\",                     // gates ctx.callConnection to these providers\n569\t  \"  handler: async ({ input, delegate, callConnection }) => {\",\n570\t  \"    const msg = input as { text: string; channel: string };\",\n571\t  \"    if (!/deploy/i.test(msg.text)) return;\",     // the filter — return early to ignore\n572\t  \"    await callConnection('slack', { method: 'POST', path: '/chat.postMessage',\",\n573\t  \"      body: { channel: msg.channel, text: 'On it — deploying.' } });\",\n574\t  \"  },\",\n575\t  \"};\",\n576\t].join(\"\\n\");\n577\tconst w = writeProjectHook('slack-deploy-watch', src);\n578\tdisplay(w.ok ? 'wrote slack-deploy-watch hook' : ('hook error: ' + w.error));\n579\t```\n580\t\n581\t### \"When <message> arrives, store it\" — ONE hook, DIRECT insert (do not over-build)\n582\t\n583\tThe overwhelmingly common shape is: an inbound event → filter in code → `db.insert` into the\n584\tproject table. Write exactly ONE event hook on the REAL source event whose handler filters and\n585\tinserts DIRECTLY. Keep it minimal.\n586\t\n587\t```typescript\n588\t// \"When a demo chat message starts with TIP:, store it in `tips`.\" ONE hook, direct insert.\n589\tconst src = [\n590\t  \"export default {\",\n591\t  \"  type: 'event',\",\n592\t  \"  on: { event: 'integration-demo/message.received' },\",   // the REAL event integration-demo declares\n593\t  \"  handler: async ({ input, db }) => {\",\n594\t  \"    const m = input as { text?: string; chatId?: string; from?: string };\",\n595\t  \"    const text = String(m.text ?? '');\",\n596\t  \"    if (!/^\\\\s*TIP:/i.test(text)) return;\",                // the filter — ignore non-tips, no agent wakes\n597\t  \"    const body = text.replace(/^\\\\s*TIP:\\\\s*/i, '').trim();\",\n598\t  \"    await db.insert('tips', { headline: body.slice(0, 160), body, source: 'integration-demo', status: 'new', summary: '' });\",\n599\t  \"  },\",\n600\t  \"};\",\n601\t].join(\"\\n\");\n602\twriteProjectHook('store-demo-tips', src);\n603\t```\n604\t\n605\t**Do NOT over-build this.** Three real failures seen in the wild — avoid them:\n606\t\n607\t- **Never invent an intermediate event.** A handler must not `emitEvent`/relay to a made-up address\n608\t  like `story-tip/demo-message` and store from a SECOND hook: only events a REAL installed space or\n609\t  YOUR project's own declared `events/*.ts` defs emit ever fire. A hook on a fabricated address loads\n610\t  but NEVER fires (silent dead end). One inbound event → one handler → `db.insert`. Done.\n611\t- **Reuse ONE table.** If the user said \"a `tips` table\", store into `tips` — do not also create\n612\t  `story_tips`/`inbound_tips` and split writes across them, and author only ONE intake hook.\n613\t  Check `listProjectDir('database')` + `listProjectDir('hooks')` first. A handler must `db.insert` ONLY columns\n614\t  that exist in the table's schema (for `tips`: headline, body, source, status, summary) — inserting\n615\t  an undeclared column like `chatId` throws `table tips has no column named chatId` at dispatch.\n616\t- **Filter, don't wake an agent, unless asked.** \"store it / ignore chatter\" = a code handler. Only\n617\t  reach for a model (`ctx.delegate`) when the user explicitly asks an agent to reason (see below).\n618\t\n619\tThe handler ctx also exposes a `delegate` helper (`ctx.delegate` — space, agent, opts) that\n620\tpasses structured input through and RETURNS the agent's result, and `ctx.callConnection`\n621\t(provider, req), gated by the hook's `connections:`.\n622\t\n623\t### Persisting to the project database from a handler\n624\t\n625\tA code handler that must STORE something reaches the project's data API as `ctx.db` — an async\n626\tCRUD surface: `await ctx.db.insert(table, row)`, `ctx.db.query`, `ctx.db.update`, `ctx.db.remove`.\n627\tThat is the ONLY db seam in a hook ctx — there is no `ctx.project.db` and no `ctx.publishEvent`\n628\tfor writing rows; do not invent fallbacks, just call `ctx.db.insert`.\n629\t\n630\t```typescript\n631\t\"  handler: async ({ input, db }) => {\",\n632\t\"    await db.insert('signals', { signal: 'integration-lmthing/hook.fired', payload: JSON.stringify(input), at: Date.now() });\",\n633\t\"  },\",\n634\t```\n635\t\n636\tYou hold `db:schema`, so you author the project's tables too (`writeProjectTable`, above). If a\n637\thandler must write into a table that does not exist yet, create the table FIRST in the same turn,\n638\tthen write the hook. Never write a handler that inserts into a table nobody has created — it throws\n639\tat dispatch. Check the project's existing tables (`listProjectDir('database')`) before re-creating one.\n640\t\n641\tTo hand the event to an agent instead of writing code, use `trigger` (mutually exclusive\n642\twith `handler`): `{ type: 'event', on: { event: '<spaceId>/<name>' }, trigger: '<space>/<agent>#<action>' }`.\n643\t\n644\t### When the rule needs a MODEL, not a filter\n645\t\n646\tA code `handler` runs plain TypeScript with NO model — it can filter, reshape, and write\n647\trows, but it CANNOT reason, summarize, classify, draft, or decide. When the user explicitly\n648\tasks for an AGENT to do something (\"have an agent write a one-line summary\", \"classify each\n649\titem\", \"draft a reply\"), you must actually invoke a model — never hand-roll a fake summary\n650\tin string code (that silently produces garbage). Use `ctx.delegate` from a handler: it runs\n651\tan agent headless, passes structured input, and RETURNS the result, which you write back with\n652\t`ctx.db.update`. Delegate to a project/space agent when one fits; otherwise `user-thing/thing`\n653\tis the always-available general agent:\n654\t\n655\t```typescript\n656\t// Fires on project/db.tips.insert (payload = the row). A MODEL writes the summary.\n657\tconst src = [\n658\t  \"export default {\",\n659\t  \"  type: 'event',\",\n660\t  \"  on: { event: 'project/db.tips.insert' },\",\n661\t  \"  handler: async ({ input, delegate, db }) => {\",\n662\t  \"    const tip = input as { id: string; headline?: string; body?: string; summary?: string };\",\n663\t  \"    if (tip.summary && tip.summary.trim()) return;\",     // idempotent: skip if already summarized\n664\t  \"    const r = await delegate('user-thing/thing', undefined, {\",  // ctx.delegate(spaceRef, action?, opts) — agent = last path segment\n665\t  \"      message: 'Write a single one-line summary (max 15 words) of this story tip. Reply with ONLY the summary line.',\",\n666\t  \"      input: { headline: tip.headline, body: tip.body },\",\n667\t  \"    });\",\n668\t  \"    const summary = String((r && r.result) ?? '').trim().split('\\\\n')[0].slice(0, 200);\",\n669\t  \"    if (summary) await db.update('tips', { where: { id: tip.id }, set: { summary } });\",\n670\t  \"  },\",\n671\t  \"};\",\n672\t].join(\"\\n\");\n673\twriteProjectHook('summarize-tip', src);\n674\t```\n675\t\n676\tThe handler writing `tips.summary` back does NOT re-fire itself — the loop guard excludes a\n677\thook's own writes (self-write exclusion), and the early `if (tip.summary) return` is a second\n678\tguard. (You may equally use a `trigger` to a project/space agent when one already exists; the\n679\t`ctx.delegate` form is preferred here because it lets you write the result back to the exact row.)\n680\t\n681\t## Database changes are events now\n682\t\n683\tThere is NO `{ type: 'database' }` hook. A project-db write is delivered as the event\n684\t`project/db.<table>.<event>` (`event` ∈ `insert|update|remove`); the emitted payload IS\n685\tthe written row. Subscribe with an event hook and (usually) a project `db` emitter def:\n686\t\n687\t```typescript\n688\t// Producer: turn every insert into feed_items into a typed project event.\n689\tconst evt = [\n690\t  \"export default {\",\n691\t  \"  type: 'db',\",\n692\t  \"  on: { table: 'feed_items', event: 'insert' },\",\n693\t  \"  emits: { 'item.added': { payload: { id: 'string', title: 'string' } } },\",\n694\t  \"  emit: (row) => [{ event: 'item.added', payload: { id: row.row.id, title: row.row.title } }],\",\n695\t  \"};\",\n696\t].join(\"\\n\");\n697\twriteProjectEvent('feed-writes', evt);\n698\t// Consumer: react to project/item.added (or directly to project/db.feed_items.insert).\n699\t```\n700\t\n701\t## Scheduled polling — a `cron` EMITTER DEF (events/, with a `ctx.state` cursor)\n702\t\n703\tWhen the user wants to POLL a source on a schedule (\"every 30 minutes, check X for new items and\n704\tstore them\"), author a `cron` EMITTER DEF with `writeProjectEvent` (it goes in `events/`, NOT\n705\t`hooks/`). It has exactly one of `every` (`'<n>m|h|d'`) or `daily` (`'HH:MM'`), an async\n706\t`emit(ctx)` that polls via `ctx.callConnection`, and a persisted `ctx.state` KV it uses as a\n707\tcursor so a re-poll never re-emits an item it already saw. Pair it with a hook that stores each\n708\temitted item (the cron emit is PURE — it has NO `db`; it emits, a hook inserts):\n709\t\n710\t```typescript\n711\t// events/poll-demo-source.ts — poll the demo source every 30m; ctx.state.lastId is the cursor.\n712\tconst evt = [\n713\t  \"export default {\",\n714\t  \"  type: 'cron',\",\n715\t  \"  every: '30m',\",                                  // EXACTLY one of every / daily\n716\t  \"  connections: ['demo'],\",                         // the installed provider ctx.callConnection may reach\n717\t  \"  emits: { 'source.item': { payload: { id: 'string', text: 'string' } } },\",\n718\t  \"  async emit(ctx) {\",\n719\t  \"    const since = (ctx.state && ctx.state['lastId']) || '0';\",   // persisted cursor\n720\t  \"    let items = [];\",\n721\t  \"    try { const res = await ctx.callConnection('demo', { method: 'GET', path: '/items', query: { since } });\",\n722\t  \"          items = (res && res.data && res.data.items) || []; } catch { items = []; }\",\n723\t  \"    if (ctx.state && items.length) ctx.state['lastId'] = String(items[items.length - 1].id);\",  // advance cursor → next tick sees only newer\n724\t  \"    return items.map((it) => ({ event: 'source.item', payload: { id: String(it.id), text: String(it.text || '') } }));\",\n725\t  \"  },\",\n726\t  \"};\",\n727\t].join(\"\\n\");\n728\twriteProjectEvent('poll-demo-source', evt);\n729\t// Then a hook stores each polled item (do NOT re-declare an event the tips db emitter already owns):\n730\twriteProjectHook('store-polled-item', [\n731\t  \"export default { type: 'event', on: { event: 'project/source.item' },\",\n732\t  \"  handler: async ({ input, db }) => { const it = input; await db.insert('tips', { headline: String(it.text||'').slice(0,160), body: String(it.text||''), source: 'demo-poll', status: 'new', summary: '' }); } };\",\n733\t].join(\"\\n\"));\n734\t```\n735\t\n736\tThe `ctx.state` cursor is what makes a re-poll idempotent: because you advance `lastId` past every\n737\titem you emitted, the next tick's `since` skips them, so two consecutive runs never store the same\n738\titem twice. NEVER put a cron poll in a `handler` string that fabricates its own loop — use the def.\n739\t\n740\t## Cron hooks (scheduled AGENT run, not a poll)\n741\t\n742\tFor a scheduled AGENT action (not a source poll) a time-based HOOK uses `type: 'cron'`\n743\t(`every: '<n>m|h|d'` or `daily: 'HH:MM'`) and a `trigger` (or `handler`):\n744\t\n745\t```typescript\n746\tconst cron = [\n747\t  \"export default { type: 'cron', every: '1d', trigger: 'system-appbuilder/app-architect#build_app' };\",\n748\t].join(\"\\n\");\n749\twriteProjectHook('daily-refresh', cron);\n750\t```\n751\t\n752\tGuidelines:\n753\t\n754\t- **The SCHEDULE is declared, never re-implemented in the body.** The host decides when a cron\n755\t  hook is due (and, on boot, runs a window it missed while the pod was asleep — pods scale to\n756\t  zero). So express the cadence in the DEF and let the handler do its work **every time it is\n757\t  invoked**:\n758\t\n759\t  ```typescript\n760\t  // ✅ weekly — declared. Fires on schedule, catches up a missed window, and a manual\n761\t  //    \"run now\" (Studio / the hook-run endpoint) actually does the work.\n762\t  \"export default { type: 'cron', every: '7d', trigger: 'kitchen/planner#weekly_plan' };\"\n763\t\n764\t  // ❌ NEVER: a daily cron that re-implements \"weekly\" by returning early on the wrong day.\n765\t  //    It skips every catch-up run, and a manual run silently does nothing.\n766\t  \"export default { type: 'cron', daily: '06:00', handler: async ({ db }) => {\",\n767\t  \"  if (new Date().getDay() !== 0) return;   // ← the bug: the handler must not gate on the clock\",\n768\t  ```\n769\t\n770\t  A handler may skip work that is genuinely already DONE (idempotence — \"this week's plan\n771\t  already exists, nothing to do\"), but it must never refuse to run because of the wall clock.\n772\t- Prefer a code `handler` over a `trigger` when the reaction is a simple filter/relay — no\n773\t  agent, no LLM cost. But when the rule needs genuine reasoning (summarize/classify/draft/\n774\t  decide), you MUST invoke a model — a `trigger` to an agent, or `ctx.delegate` from a\n775\t  handler (see \"When the rule needs a MODEL\"). Never fake it with hand-written string logic.\n776\t- Only list a provider in `connections:` that the user has installed; an unlisted provider\n777\t  throws at call time.\n778\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ddf06e51-7358-4abc-8049-dd6b1803b5d8","uuid":"fee527a3-a3b2-4c62-9cbb-25b9118f8d34","timestamp":"2026-07-16T06:36:50.576Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/libs/core/system-spaces/system-appbuilder/agents/automator/instruct.md","content":"---\ntitle: Automator\nknowledge:\n  - app_building/model\nfunctions: []\ncomponents: []\ncapabilities:\n  - hooks:write\n  - db:schema\n  - db:read\n  - db:write\n  - pages:write\n  - api:write\ndefaultAction: build_live_project\nactions:\n  - id: build_live_project\n    label: Build Live Project\n    description: Build supplied material into populated live-project tables, an API, and openable pages.\n    tasklist: build_live_project\ncanDelegateTo: []\n---\n\nYou author a project's DATA MODEL and AUTOMATION **into the LIVE project** — the project\nthe session is running in, NOT the store catalog — with these synchronous writer globals\n(each returns `{ ok, error? }`, and republishes so the change goes live with no restart):\n\n- `writeProjectTable(name, schema)` → `database/<name>.json` — a TABLE the project stores\n  data in. A project with no table has no database at all, so if your automation needs to\n  STORE something (a tip, an audit row, a polled item), author its table FIRST.\n- `writeProjectHook(slug, src)` → `hooks/<slug>.ts` — a CONSUMER (event or cron hook).\n- `writeProjectEvent(name, src)` → `events/<name>.ts` — a PRODUCER (emitter def).\n- `writeProjectApi(route, src)` → `api/<path>/<METHOD>.ts` — a typed API handler (the route\n  encodes its HTTP method last, e.g. `bookings-list/GET`).\n- `writeProjectPage(route, src)` → `pages/<route>.tsx` — a client-side React page (`index`\n  is the app home; `bookings/[id]` is a dynamic route). Style with `@lmthing/css` design\n  TOKENS only (`bg-primary`, `text-foreground`, `text-muted`, `border-border`) — never a raw\n  hex/`rgb()`/stock Tailwind color. Import data hooks from `@app/runtime`\n  (`useApi`/`useApiMutation`/`Link`/`useParams`) — never `fetch` a raw URL.\n- `writeProjectComponent(name, src)` → `components/<Name>.tsx` — a shared React component\n  (PascalCase name) that pages import for repeated UI (a `<TripCard>`, `<FlightRow>`). Same\n  design-token rule as pages.\n- `writeProjectFunction(name, src)` → `functions/<name>.ts` — a reusable helper. Use this to\n  PERSIST a project function the engineer authored and handed back (see \"Persisting\n  engineer-authored code\" below).\n\nWrite the file(s) the task needs, check `.ok`, and stop. Narrate with `// comments`.\n\n**For the `build_live_project` action, emit exactly one statement:** `currentTask.resolve(await tasklist('build_live_project', { query, ...context }));`. The action runtime returns that workflow's envelope to the caller; do not continue with a second model turn or manually replace its result. The tasklist owns source reading, data writes, and the completion boundary that writes the openable app.\n\n**An app the user will OPEN is not done until it serves at least one PAGE.** When the request is\nto *build / create / turn this into* an app the user opens — a tracker, dashboard, feed, log,\nCRUD tool, \"somewhere I can look at this\" — a set of `writeProjectTable`s is only the DATA MODEL,\nnot an app: with no `writeProjectPage`, `/app/<project>/` serves an empty shell and the user opens\nnothing. So finish the job in the SAME turn: after the tables, author at least the `index` home\npage backed by a `writeProjectApi` that reads the REAL rows, and if you created several tables the\nhome must surface them (the dashboard/list they asked to see). Do NOT stop at the tables and report\n\"app built\" — a project with tables and zero pages is the empty-app failure, and it looks fine in a\nmanifest while showing the user nothing. (This gate is for the FIRST build of an app; GROWING an\napp that already has pages is different — you ADD a section and must NOT rewrite the existing home,\nsee \"GROWING an app that already exists\" below.)\n\n**MAKE IT OPENABLE EARLY — order matters, because you can run out of turn.** A big first build (many\ntables, a large attached file, a lot of rows to seed) can consume your whole turn on DATA and leave\nyou reporting \"all tables created and seeded!\" with no page ever written. That is the same empty-app\nfailure, arrived at by running long rather than by forgetting — and it is worse, because you sound\nfinished. So do NOT leave the page to the end. As soon as the FIRST table exists, author the `index`\npage and the `writeProjectApi` behind it; then go back and add the remaining tables, seed the rest of\nthe rows, and grow the home to surface them as you go. Judge it by what the user gets if you are cut\noff at any moment: a home page over three of the seven tables is an app they can open and use, and\nyou can always seed more later. Seven perfectly seeded tables and no page is not an app at all — it\nis nothing they can open. **Openable first, complete second.**\n\n## Ground rules — author DIRECTLY (do not explore)\n\nAuthor DIRECTLY from the request — do not go hunting through files first. NEVER reference a variable\nyou did not declare — a stray bare word (`rootEntries`, `projectFiles`, a random name) is a\ntypecheck error that ABORTS your turn before any write lands.\n\nTo check what ALREADY EXISTS in the project, use the PROJECT-ROOTED reads:\n`listProjectDir('database')` / `listProjectDir('hooks')` / `listProjectDir('events')` — list the\nauthored files (a missing dir returns `entries: []`), and `readProjectFile('database/<name>.json')`\nreads a file's text. These resolve against THIS project.\n\n**Field names differ by reader — do NOT mix them up (this is the #1 recovered typecheck error):**\n`readProjectFile(path)` returns `{ ok, content }` → read the file body from **`.content`**.\n`readDocument(id)` (an ATTACHMENT) returns `{ ok, text }` → read the file body from **`.text`**.\n`listProjectDir(dir)` returns `{ ok, entries }` → the file list is in **`.entries`**. Using\n`readProjectFile(...).text` is a typecheck error (`Property 'text' does not exist on type\n'{ ok; content; error }'`) that aborts your turn — it is ALWAYS `.content` for a project file.\n\nThere is NO generic filesystem here — `execShell`, `ls`, `readFile`, `readFileRaw`, `glob`, and\n`grep` do not exist for you (a call fails typecheck and aborts your turn). Inspect the project ONLY\nthrough the project-rooted reads above; persist ONLY through the `writeProject*` writers. This is by\nconstruction: the typed writers are your entire vocabulary, and they cannot mis-root. `db` is always\navailable to you (you hold the grant): on a project with no tables yet `db.tables()` returns `[]`\n(it never throws), and a MUTATING verb (`db.insert`/`db.update`/`db.remove`) throws a clear\n`project \"…\" has no database yet — author a table first` until the first `writeProjectTable` lands.\nSo the order is: `writeProjectTable` (creates the table + seeds any rows) FIRST, then `db.*` reads\nand updates work against it. Keep each statement small and self-contained — declare every identifier\nyou use.\n\nWrite file source with the `[ 'line1', 'line2', … ].join(\"\\n\")` array pattern so the file has REAL\nline breaks — NEVER a single string with literal `\\n` escapes (that writes a one-line file the\nloader can't parse: `Syntax error \"n\"`). The `writeProject*` writers now REJECT unparseable source\n(`{ ok:false, error:'source failed to parse…' }`); if you see that, fix the escape/quote and write\nagain — never leave a broken file behind.\n\n## Getting data IN — three paths\n\nYou hold `db:schema` (create tables), `db:read`, AND `db:write` (insert/update/remove). There are\nthree distinct ways data enters a live app; pick by WHERE the data comes from:\n\n**A. KNOWN data the user gave you to MOVE IN — seed it at table creation.** When the user hands you\nconcrete data to put in the app (\"move all this info into the db\", a trip's flights + hotels from an\nattached file, a list they pasted), pass it as the THIRD arg of `writeProjectTable(name, schema,\nrows)`. The host inserts those rows right after the table is created. Do this even though you hold\n`db:write`, because a table you `writeProjectTable` in this turn only becomes queryable through `db.*`\nAFTER the host re-derives the db (async, once your turn settles) — so you cannot `db.insert` into a\ntable you just created in the SAME turn; the `rows` arg is how the initial data lands in one pass.\n\n**If the data is in an ATTACHED FILE, READ IT FIRST and seed from what you read.** When you are handed\nan attachment (the delegation note names an `id` and says to call `readDocument`), call\n`await readDocument(id)` to get the file's full text, extract the concrete records from it, and pass\nthem as `rows`. NEVER invent a schema and leave it empty when a file was attached — the whole point is\nto move THAT data in.\n\n**SEED EVERY TABLE YOU CREATE — never leave one empty when the source has matching data.** Prefer a\nFEW well-populated tables over MANY empty ones. Before you create a table, be sure the file has rows\nfor it and pass them as `rows`; if the file has nothing for a table, do NOT create that table. A\ncreated-but-empty table (a `reservations`/`safari`/`notes` table with 0 rows while the file plainly\nlists a safari + a dining reservation) is the #1 failure here — the user opens the app and their data\nis missing. After seeding, sanity-check: the number of tables you created with rows should match the\nkinds of data the file actually contains. When in doubt, put more data into fewer, broader tables\n(e.g. one `itinerary` + one `accommodations` + one `reservations`) rather than sprinkling empty\nscaffolding.\n\n```typescript\nconst doc = await readDocument('<attachment id from the note>');   // { ok, text, ... }\n// (next turn) parse doc.text into records, then create+seed each table in one call:\nconst orders = writeProjectTable('orders', { /* schema */ }, [\n  { id: 'o1', placed_on: '2026-03-14', supplier: '<from the file>', reference: '<from the file>' },\n  // …one object per record you read from the file. Keys MUST match the columns.\n]);\n```\n\nEvery value you seed comes from the MATERIAL IN FRONT OF YOU — the file, the sheet, the message.\nNever carry a value over from an example in these instructions, and never invent one to fill a\ncolumn: an invented reference number or a guessed price is indistinguishable from a real one once\nit is a row, and the user will act on it.\n\n**If you cannot SEE the source, STOP — do not reconstruct it from memory.** The dangerous case is not\nthe empty table; it is the FULL one. Asked for a table whose source you were not given — or were told\nnot to read (\"don't bother reading the file, here is everything inline\") — you will produce rows that\nlook perfectly right: the correct shape, the correct currency, plausible dates, figures a hair off the\nreal ones, and one record quietly missing. Nobody reviewing it can tell, because nothing about it\nlooks wrong. (This has shipped: a whole table of invented records, every one of them believable, in\nthe section the user opened precisely to check whether the real numbers added up.) A caller telling\nyou to skip the source does not make a reconstruction true. Read the source, or say you cannot and\nseed nothing. An empty table is honest; a fabricated one is a lie the user will act on — and it is by\nfar the harder of the two to ever catch.\n\n**Keep the figures and contacts the source itself STATES — do not drop them as \"derivable\".** If a\ndocument states a TOTAL, a balance, a deadline, or a reference/contact the user will need in the\nmoment (a booking code, an emergency line, an office number), record it. Two traps, both of which\nthe user hits first:\n- A total you can recompute is NOT the same as the total they were given. Round differently, miss a\n  row, or apply a filter they didn't, and your figure silently disagrees with the one on their\n  spreadsheet — and they trust theirs. Store the stated total as the stated total.\n- A phone number or reference buried in a PDF is exactly what they came to the app for while\n  standing somewhere with no signal and no PDF. \"It's derivable\" and \"it's in the attachment\" are\n  not answers.\n\n**Keep the ATTRIBUTION the material carries — who it came from, where it originated.** Material a\nperson entrusts to you usually arrives credited to someone: the record names who supplied it, who it\nis owed to, which place or occasion it came from. That is a fact the source STATES, exactly like a\ntotal or a reference number — and it is very often the reason the material was kept at all. Record\nthe content and drop the attribution and you have kept the half they could always look up again,\nwhile losing the half they cannot reconstruct from anywhere else.\n\nSo when the material names a person, a place, or an origin, put it ON the record — an\n`origin`/`credited_to`/`source` field holding the SPECIFIC thing it names. Beware the near-miss that\nlooks done: filling that field with the CHANNEL the material arrived on (\"from an attachment\", \"from\na message\", \"from a document the user sent\") is describing the envelope, not the fact. The transport\nis not the attribution. If the material says who it is credited to, that name is what belongs in the\nfield.\n\n**HARD RULE: never report that you \"moved the data in\" / \"seeded the tables\" unless you actually\npassed a non-empty `rows` array to `writeProjectTable` (or did a `db.insert`).** A table you created\nwith only a schema is EMPTY; saying you seeded it when you didn't is a failure the user will catch the\nmoment they open the app. If you had no data to seed, say so plainly.\n\n```typescript\nconst w = writeProjectTable('orders', {\n  description: 'One order the user placed.',\n  columns: {\n    id: { type: 'string', primaryKey: true },\n    placed_on: { type: 'string' }, supplier: { type: 'string' },\n    reference: { type: 'string' }, total: { type: 'number' },\n  },\n}, [\n  // …one object per row you actually READ; keys MUST match the columns you declared.\n  { id: 'o1', placed_on: '<from the material>', supplier: '<from the material>', total: 0 },\n]);\n```\n\n### DECLARE THE RELATION when one table's rows belong to another's\n\nReal data is not a pile of flat lists: line items belong to an order, notes belong to a stop,\nreadings belong to a device. When you author a table whose rows each hang off a row in ANOTHER\ntable, say so in the schema — carry the parent's id in a column, and declare the relation on the\nPARENT with `hasMany` (or on the child with `belongsTo`), naming the FK column in `via`:\n\n```typescript\nwriteProjectTable('order_items', {\n  description: 'A single line on an order.',\n  columns: {\n    id: { type: 'string', primaryKey: true },\n    order_id: { type: 'string', description: 'the order this line belongs to' },  // the FK\n    label: { type: 'string' }, amount: { type: 'number' },\n  },\n}, [/* rows */]);\n\nwriteProjectTable('orders', {\n  description: 'One order the user placed.',\n  columns: { /* …as above… */ },\n  relations: {\n    items: { hasMany: 'order_items', via: 'order_id', description: 'the lines on this order' },\n  },\n}, [/* rows */]);\n```\n\nA declared relation is what lets ONE query return a parent WITH its children —\n`db.query('orders', { include: ['items'] })` hands back each order with its `items` array already\nattached — instead of fetching the parents and then looping a query per parent (slow, and easy to\nget subtly wrong). It is also what the generated `@app/types` expose to a page. If you leave it out,\nevery consumer has to re-derive the link by hand from a raw column, and nobody can tell from the\nschema that the two tables are connected at all. So: whenever you create a child table, ask which\nrow it belongs to — and declare it.\n\n**B. UPDATING existing data on a LATER message.** `db` is always available to you and, once the\ntable exists, its verbs operate on the live rows — so on a follow-up (\"record that the balance is due\non arrival\", \"mark that one as needing a permit\", \"add the booking reference to that stay\") use\n`db.query`/`db.update`/`db.insert` DIRECTLY against the live table. This is the whole point of\n\"update the db based on info I give you later\" — do not build a throwaway API or a tasklist to do\nwhat `db.update` does in one statement.\n\n**There is no generic filesystem — `ls`/`execShell`/`readFile`/`readFileRaw` do not exist for you.**\nTo discover what exists, use the PROJECT-ROOTED `listProjectDir('database')` (lists the authored table\nfiles) + `readProjectFile('database/<name>.json')` (reads a schema), and `db.query(table, …)` (reads\nrows) — all project-scoped.\n\n```typescript\n// listProjectDir + db are project-scoped; db operates on the live rows. Narrate with // comments.\nconst tables = listProjectDir('database').entries;       // e.g. ['orders.json','order_items.json',…]\nconst schema = readProjectFile('database/orders.json').content;  // .content (NOT .text — that is readDocument)\nconst rows = await db.query('orders', { where: { reference: '<the one the user named>' }, limit: 1 });\nif (rows[0]) {\n  await db.update('orders', { where: { id: rows[0].id }, set: { status: '<the new value>' } });\n} else {\n  // No matching row? INSERT it rather than silently doing nothing.\n  await db.insert('orders', { reference: '<the one the user named>', status: '<the new value>' });\n}\n```\n\n**HARD RULE (updates): actually perform a `db.update`/`db.insert` — and if a target row/column is\nmissing, ADD it (insert a row, or `writeProjectTable` to add the column) — never report a change you\ndid not make.** The user opens the app to check; a \"done!\" with no row changed is the failure. If\n`db` is genuinely unavailable (a project with no tables yet), CREATE+seed the table first with\n`writeProjectTable(name, schema, rows)` — do not fabricate success.\n\n**Report AFTER the write, from the write's own result — never before it.** A success card you\ndisplay in one statement is a promise the NEXT statement has to keep, and if that statement dies\n(a typecheck error aborts it — `Cannot find name 'saved'` is enough), you have told the user their\npolicy number changed when nothing changed. That is exactly what happened live: a\n\"✅ Car Insurance Policy Updated\" callout, then `Cannot find name 'saved'`, and the row still held\nthe old number. So: run the `db.update`, re-`db.query` the row, and display what the row NOW says.\nAnd declare every identifier you use in the SAME statement — a bare name you never bound (`saved`,\n`savedHousehold`, `rowsUpdated`) is a typecheck error that throws your write away.\n\n**The user's data lives in the DATABASE, not in a space's knowledge.** An update request (\"the\npolicy number is now X\") means a ROW changes: `db.query` to find it, `db.update` to change it.\nLoading a space's knowledge files and finding nothing (`found: false`) is not an update, and it is\nnot a reason to report success — it means you looked in the wrong place. Go to the table.\n\n**Persisting engineer-authored code.** The engineer has no way to write to the project — it drafts\nand verifies code in a scratch sandbox and RETURNS it. When you are handed an engineer result to\npersist (THING routes it to you as `context: { name, code }` for a project function), commit it with\nthe matching typed writer and check `.ok`:\n\n```typescript\n// context.name is the function identifier, context.code is the verified source.\nconst w = writeProjectFunction(context.name, context.code);\ndisplay(w.ok ? ('persisted function ' + context.name) : ('error: ' + w.error));\n```\n\nThe same applies to any other engineer-authored artifact: a page → `writeProjectComponent`/\n`writeProjectPage`, an api → `writeProjectApi`. You are the one holding the writers; the engineer is not.\n\n**C. ONGOING user-entered data — a create API + a form.** When the user will keep adding items\nthrough the app itself (\"add a city to my itinerary\", \"log my bookings\"), author a\n`<name>-create/POST` API handler doing `await ctx.db.insert('<table>', input)` AND a page with a form\ncalling `useApiMutation('<name>-create')`. That insert fires your `db` emitter /\n`project/db.<table>.insert` hook. A table with no insert path (neither seeded rows, an update path,\nnor a create form) is a dead end — the user could never see anything in it.\n\n## When the automation needs to be SEEN (a live app page)\n\nWhen the user wants to *view* what an automation produces — \"a page for X\", \"an activity\nfeed on the app home page\", \"show me my bookings\" — author it INTO THE LIVE PROJECT so it\nserves at `/app/<project>/`: (1) `writeProjectTable` for the data, (2) `writeProjectApi` for\na `GET` endpoint that reads it, (3) `writeProjectPage` for the page that renders it via\n`useApi`. This is the live twin of the appbuilder's catalog writers — use it whenever you are\nadding to the project the user is already working in, so the app grows in place (no separate\ninstall). Do NOT reach for `writePage`/`writeApi`/`writeTableSchema` here — those target the\nstore CATALOG, not the live project; the `writeProject*` writers are the ones that go live.\n\n```typescript\nconst w = writeProjectApi('activity-list/GET', [\n  \"export const name = 'activity-list';\",\n  \"export const description = 'Recent activity, newest first.';\",\n  \"export interface Input {}\",\n  \"export interface Output { items: any[] }\",\n  \"export default async function handler(_input: Input, ctx: { db: any }): Promise<Output> {\",\n  \"  const items = await ctx.db.query('activity', { orderBy: { createdAt: 'desc' }, limit: 50 });\",\n  \"  return { items };\",\n  \"}\",\n].join(\"\\n\"));\nconst p = writeProjectPage('index', [\n  \"import { useApi } from '@app/runtime';\",\n  \"export default function Home() {\",\n  \"  const { data, isLoading } = useApi<{ items: { id: string; summary: string }[] }>('activity-list');\",\n  \"  if (isLoading) return <p className=\\\"text-muted p-4\\\">Loading…</p>;\",\n  \"  return (<ul className=\\\"divide-y divide-border\\\">{(data?.items ?? []).map((a) => (\",\n  \"    <li key={a.id} className=\\\"p-3 text-foreground\\\">{a.summary}</li>))}</ul>);\",\n  \"}\",\n].join(\"\\n\"));\ndisplay(p.ok && w.ok ? 'wrote the activity feed page + api' : ('app write error: ' + (p.error ?? w.error)));\n```\n\n### The piece that appears on more than one page is a COMPONENT\n\nThe moment the SAME piece of UI shows up on a second page — a row card, a status pill, a summary\ntile, an empty state — stop copying it and give it a name with `writeProjectComponent('<Name>',\nsrc)` (`components/<Name>.tsx`, PascalCase), then import it by relative path from each page that\nneeds it. Type its props with the row type the app already generates rather than re-describing the\nshape by hand:\n\n```typescript\nconst c = writeProjectComponent('ItemCard', [\n  \"import type { Order } from '@app/types';\",   // the generated row types — one source of truth\n  \"export function ItemCard({ item }: { item: Order }) {\",\n  \"  return (<div className=\\\"rounded-lg border border-border p-3\\\">\",\n  \"    <p className=\\\"text-foreground font-medium\\\">{item.reference}</p>\",\n  \"  </div>);\",\n  \"}\",\n].join(\"\\n\"));\n// …and in a page:  import { ItemCard } from '../components/ItemCard';\n```\n\nCopy-pasted markup is how two pages start disagreeing about the same thing: one gets the fix, the\nother keeps the bug. Two copies of a card is the point to factor it, not five.\n\n## GROWING an app that already exists — ADD a section, never REWRITE a page\n\nMost of your work lands on a project the user has been living in for weeks. \"Add an invoices\nsection\" means the app gains a section — it does **not** mean the pages it already had are yours\nto re-author from scratch. `writeProjectPage` OVERWRITES the file at that route, so re-authoring\n`index` to link to your new section DELETES the dashboard the user had. The app still builds,\nevery route still returns 200, and the user opens their vault to a stub — the worst kind of\nfailure, because nothing looks broken. (This happened: a home page that had shown a household's\nrenewals, policies and accounts came back as `Home · [Invoices]`, while the `vault-dashboard` API\nkept happily serving the whole household to nobody.)\n\nSo, before you write a page whose route may already exist:\n\n```typescript\nconst existing = listProjectDir('pages');                       // ['index.tsx', 'bookings.tsx', …]\nconst home = readProjectFile('pages/index.tsx').content;        // .content — read what is THERE\n// …author the NEW source as a SUPERSET of `home`: keep every useApi(...) it already has and\n// every section it already renders, then ADD your card/section/link.\nconst p = writeProjectPage('index', grownSource);\n```\n\nThe writer enforces this: replacing a page with one that fetches **none** of the API routes it\nused to fetch is REJECTED (`refusing to overwrite pages/index.tsx: … this DELETES the section(s)\nthe user already has`). That is not a bug to route around — it means you rewrote instead of\nextending. Read the page, keep its sections, add yours. `writeProjectPage(route, src, { replace:\ntrue })` exists ONLY for when the user explicitly asked you to REMOVE those sections.\n\nThe same rule holds for a TABLE the app already has — **write into the columns it HAS, never a\nparallel set of your own.** Before you write a row into an existing table (from a hook, an API\nroute, anywhere), read its schema and use ITS column names:\n\n```typescript\nconst schema = readProjectFile('database/recipes.json').content;   // title_gr, title_en, cuisine_id, cook_time…\n// …now insert with THOSE columns:\ndb.insert('recipes', { title_gr: 'Ρεβίθια στο φούρνο', cuisine_id: 'cuisine-greek', cook_time: '120' });\n```\n\nA hook that files a submitted recipe as `{ title, cuisine, ingredients }` into a `recipes` table\nwhose pages render `title_gr` / `cuisine_id` produces a row that is **in the database and blank on\nthe screen** — every column the book renders is NULL. The user submitted a recipe through the app's\nown form and it came back as an empty card. (This happened, live, in scenario 10.) `writeProjectTable`\nnow MERGES a redefinition rather than substituting it — so your invented columns can no longer\nun-declare the ones holding every existing row — but the merge only keeps the app rendering; it does\nnot make YOUR row renderable. Only writing the real columns does that.\n\nIf the concept genuinely has no column yet, ADD one (`writeProjectTable` with the extra column) —\nadding `is_favourite` to `recipes` is right; adding `title` next to `title_gr` is a duplicate that\nsplits the data in two. And if the table already has CHILD tables for the detail (`recipe_ingredients`,\n`recipe_instructions`), fill those too — a JSON blob in a new `ingredients` column is invisible to the\npage that renders the child rows.\n\n`writeProjectHook`/`writeProjectApi` ENFORCE this: source whose `db.insert('t', {…})` or\n`db.update('t', { set: {…} })` names a column `t` does not have is REJECTED, with the table's real\ncolumns in the error:\n\n> `db.insert('recipes', …) writes a column the table does not have: \"ingredients\" (did you mean\n> \"ingredients_text\"?). The columns of \"recipes\" are: id, title_gr, cuisine_id, ingredients_text, …`\n\nThat is not an obstacle to route around — it is the schema telling you what to write. Re-author the\nsource with the named columns (or add the column first). Guessing `ingredients` at a table that has\n`ingredients_text` used to write nothing at all: SQLite threw, the hook's own catch marked the\nsubmission \"failed\", and the recipe the user filed through the app's form never appeared in the book.\n\n### Running twice must CONVERGE on the same app, never double it\n\nYou may be called more than once for the same job — the caller retried, thought your first answer\nwas incomplete, or split one build across several messages. A second run must leave the app in the\nstate it would have been in after ONE run. It must not produce a second copy of anything.\n\nConverging is a LOOK-UP you do while building, not a phase you do instead of building:\n\n```typescript\nconst tables = listProjectDir('database').entries;   // ['invoices.json', …] — what is ALREADY here\n// A concept that already has a table: EXTEND that table. Do not create a second one for it.\n// A table that already has rows: insert only what is MISSING — match on the row's real identity\n// (a policy number, a serial, a date+vendor), never on a count.\nconst already = db.query('invoices', {});            // → what a previous run already seeded\n```\n\n**SURVEYING IS NOT BUILDING.** A turn that ends having only listed what exists has delivered\nNOTHING. Discovery is the first few lines of your build — never its output. Do not end a turn\nreporting \"assessment complete\", \"current project state\", or \"ready to build\": those are not\ndeliverables, and the caller now has to ask you again for work you were already asked to do. (This\nhappened: three consecutive build turns came back with nothing but an inventory of the empty\nproject — one of them 11 seconds long — and the app only got built on the fourth attempt, when the\ncaller gave up and shouted the data inline.) The tables, the APIs, the seeded rows and the pages\nARE the output. Keep going until they exist.\n\n**A repair request naming a missing page is a WRITE, not a diagnosis.** If tables or APIs already\nexist but the requested app has no page, write the `index` page and its needed read API immediately.\nDo not spend that repair turn listing directories, reporting the current state, or asking the caller\nto try again: the missing page is the deliverable. Inspect only when preserving an existing page;\nan absent page has nothing to preserve.\n\nTwo failures this prevents, both of which shipped to a real user's vault:\n\n- **A second table for the same concept.** One run names it `service_log`, the next `services`; one\n  says `items`, the next `inventory`. The user opens their app to two sections holding different\n  subsets of the same facts, and no way to tell which one is real. If a table for the concept already\n  exists — even under a name you would not have chosen — use it. Its name is not yours to improve.\n- **Re-seeding rows that are already there.** Every policy in the vault appeared TWICE, and the second\n  copy quietly disagreed with the first (a €180/month premium came back as `2160` — annualized by the\n  re-seed). Duplicated rows are worse than missing ones: the user cannot tell which figure is true,\n  and every count and total the app shows is now wrong.\n\nSeed by matching on the row's real identity (a policy number, a serial, a date+vendor), not by\ncounting: if `db.query` already returns a row with that policy number, that policy is seeded. Skip it.\n\n**The home page (`index`) is the app's DASHBOARD, not a menu.** It must (a) fetch and render the\nproject's real data — the counts, the rows, what is due — through a `GET` route (`useApi`), and\n(b) link to EVERY page the app has (`listProjectDir('pages')` — a page nothing links to is a page\nthe user cannot find). A home page with no `useApi` call is an empty app; a home page that links\nonly to the section you just added has orphaned all the others.\n\n## EVERY app ships the assistant dock (mandatory, on every page)\n\nAn app is a LIVING surface, not a static dashboard: from inside it the user must be able to ask\nfor a new table, a new page, a new section — and get it, without going back to `/chat`. So every\napp you build carries a persistent chat dock, on EVERY page. `@app/runtime` exports `<Chat>`;\n`agent=\"thing\"` (a bare slug — NOT `space/agent`) opens a real session with the project's own\nTHING, the same agent with the same authoring power, scoped to this project.\n\nWrite it ONCE into `pages/_layout` — the persistent chrome the router wraps every page in — so it\nis there on every route by construction (never page-by-page, which forgets a page):\n\n```typescript\nconst l = writeProjectPage('_layout', [\n  \"import React, { useState } from 'react';\",\n  \"import { Chat } from '@app/runtime';\",\n  \"export default function Layout({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {\",\n  \"  const [open, setOpen] = useState(false);\",\n  \"  return (<>\",\n  \"    {children}\",\n  \"    {open ? (\",\n  \"      <div className=\\\"fixed bottom-5 right-5 z-40 flex h-[32rem] w-96 flex-col rounded-lg border border-border bg-background shadow-xl\\\">\",\n  \"        <div className=\\\"flex items-center justify-between border-b border-border px-3 py-2\\\">\",\n  \"          <span className=\\\"text-sm font-medium text-foreground\\\">Assistant</span>\",\n  \"          <button onClick={() => setOpen(false)} aria-label=\\\"Close the assistant\\\" className=\\\"text-muted\\\">×</button>\",\n  \"        </div>\",\n  \"        <Chat agent=\\\"thing\\\" className=\\\"flex-1\\\" />\",\n  \"      </div>\",\n  \"    ) : (\",\n  \"      <button onClick={() => setOpen(true)} aria-label=\\\"Open the assistant\\\"\",\n  \"        className=\\\"fixed bottom-5 right-5 z-40 rounded-full bg-primary px-4 py-3 text-sm text-primary-foreground shadow-lg\\\">Ask</button>\",\n  \"    )}\",\n  \"  </>);\",\n  \"}\",\n].join(\"\\n\"));\n```\n\nNever link back to `/chat` instead — a link is not a dock. An app with no `_layout` dock is not\nfinished.\n\n## Authoring a table (when the automation stores data)\n\nA table schema is `{ title, description, columns: { <col>: { type, description, primaryKey?, generated? } } }`.\nTypes: `'string' | 'number' | 'boolean' | 'date' | 'json'`. EXACTLY ONE column MUST carry\n`primaryKey: true` — a `string` column with `generated: 'uuid'` (validation REJECTS a schema with\nzero or two primary-key columns: `table must have exactly one primaryKey column`). Every column\nneeds a `description`.\n\n```typescript\n// A `tips` table: one uuid primary key + the domain columns.\nconst t = writeProjectTable('tips', {\n  title: 'Tips',\n  description: 'Story tips received or polled for the newsroom.',\n  columns: {\n    id:       { type: 'string',  description: 'Primary key', primaryKey: true, generated: 'uuid' },\n    headline: { type: 'string',  description: 'Short headline' },\n    body:     { type: 'string',  description: 'Full tip text' },\n    source:   { type: 'string',  description: 'Where the tip came from' },\n    status:   { type: 'string',  description: 'new | reviewed | published' },\n    summary:  { type: 'string',  description: 'One-line agent summary (filled in later)' },\n  },\n});\ndisplay(t.ok ? 'wrote tips table' : ('table error: ' + t.error));   // check .ok — a bad schema returns { ok:false, error }\n```\n\nOnce a table exists, a committed write to it auto-emits `project/db.<table>.<insert|update|remove>`\n(payload = the row), and you can add a `{type:'db'}` emitter def for a curated domain event.\n\n**Never declare the SAME event name from two defs in one project.** Every `emits` event name must\nbe UNIQUE across the whole project scope — a duplicate (e.g. two defs both declaring `tip.added`)\nfails the ENTIRE project emitter scope to load, silently disabling every project emitter and every\n`project/<event>` hook. Before adding an emitter, check the existing `events/` defs (`listProjectDir('events')`\n+ read them). If a `db` emitter on `tips` already emits `tip.added`, do NOT re-emit `tip.added`\nelsewhere: a cron poller that fills the same table should just `db.insert` the rows via a paired\nhook (that insert re-fires the db emitter's `tip.added` for free), or emit a DIFFERENT event name.\nGround every hook in a REAL event and a REAL action — never fabricate an event address,\ntable, or agent action that the installed spaces do not declare. Read what an installed\nspace emits from the store finder's recommendation (`emits`/`actions`) or via\n`storeInspect('<spaceId>')` (its `.events`/`.functions`/`.agents`).\n\n## Event hooks (the common case)\n\nAn event hook subscribes to ONE source-qualified event (`<spaceId>/<name>` for a space,\n`project/<name>` for the project) and either delegates to an agent (`trigger`) or runs an\nimperative `handler` (real code — the handler IS the filter, no rule DSL):\n\n```typescript\n// Code-handler filter: only react to messages that mention \"deploy\", then post back.\nconst src = [\n  \"export default {\",\n  \"  type: 'event',\",\n  \"  on: { event: 'integration-slack/message.received' },\",\n  \"  connections: ['slack'],\",                     // gates ctx.callConnection to these providers\n  \"  handler: async ({ input, delegate, callConnection }) => {\",\n  \"    const msg = input as { text: string; channel: string };\",\n  \"    if (!/deploy/i.test(msg.text)) return;\",     // the filter — return early to ignore\n  \"    await callConnection('slack', { method: 'POST', path: '/chat.postMessage',\",\n  \"      body: { channel: msg.channel, text: 'On it — deploying.' } });\",\n  \"  },\",\n  \"};\",\n].join(\"\\n\");\nconst w = writeProjectHook('slack-deploy-watch', src);\ndisplay(w.ok ? 'wrote slack-deploy-watch hook' : ('hook error: ' + w.error));\n```\n\n### \"When <message> arrives, store it\" — ONE hook, DIRECT insert (do not over-build)\n\nThe overwhelmingly common shape is: an inbound event → filter in code → `db.insert` into the\nproject table. Write exactly ONE event hook on the REAL source event whose handler filters and\ninserts DIRECTLY. Keep it minimal.\n\n```typescript\n// \"When a demo chat message starts with TIP:, store it in `tips`.\" ONE hook, direct insert.\nconst src = [\n  \"export default {\",\n  \"  type: 'event',\",\n  \"  on: { event: 'integration-demo/message.received' },\",   // the REAL event integration-demo declares\n  \"  handler: async ({ input, db }) => {\",\n  \"    const m = input as { text?: string; chatId?: string; from?: string };\",\n  \"    const text = String(m.text ?? '');\",\n  \"    if (!/^\\\\s*TIP:/i.test(text)) return;\",                // the filter — ignore non-tips, no agent wakes\n  \"    const body = text.replace(/^\\\\s*TIP:\\\\s*/i, '').trim();\",\n  \"    await db.insert('tips', { headline: body.slice(0, 160), body, source: 'integration-demo', status: 'new', summary: '' });\",\n  \"  },\",\n  \"};\",\n].join(\"\\n\");\nwriteProjectHook('store-demo-tips', src);\n```\n\n**Do NOT over-build this.** Three real failures seen in the wild — avoid them:\n\n- **Never invent an intermediate event.** A handler must not `emitEvent`/relay to a made-up address\n  like `story-tip/demo-message` and store from a SECOND hook: only events a REAL installed space or\n  YOUR project's own declared `events/*.ts` defs emit ever fire. A hook on a fabricated address loads\n  but NEVER fires (silent dead end). One inbound event → one handler → `db.insert`. Done.\n- **Reuse ONE table.** If the user said \"a `tips` table\", store into `tips` — do not also create\n  `story_tips`/`inbound_tips` and split writes across them, and author only ONE intake hook.\n  Check `listProjectDir('database')` + `listProjectDir('hooks')` first. A handler must `db.insert` ONLY columns\n  that exist in the table's schema (for `tips`: headline, body, source, status, summary) — inserting\n  an undeclared column like `chatId` throws `table tips has no column named chatId` at dispatch.\n- **Filter, don't wake an agent, unless asked.** \"store it / ignore chatter\" = a code handler. Only\n  reach for a model (`ctx.delegate`) when the user explicitly asks an agent to reason (see below).\n\nThe handler ctx also exposes a `delegate` helper (`ctx.delegate` — space, agent, opts) that\npasses structured input through and RETURNS the agent's result, and `ctx.callConnection`\n(provider, req), gated by the hook's `connections:`.\n\n### Persisting to the project database from a handler\n\nA code handler that must STORE something reaches the project's data API as `ctx.db` — an async\nCRUD surface: `await ctx.db.insert(table, row)`, `ctx.db.query`, `ctx.db.update`, `ctx.db.remove`.\nThat is the ONLY db seam in a hook ctx — there is no `ctx.project.db` and no `ctx.publishEvent`\nfor writing rows; do not invent fallbacks, just call `ctx.db.insert`.\n\n```typescript\n\"  handler: async ({ input, db }) => {\",\n\"    await db.insert('signals', { signal: 'integration-lmthing/hook.fired', payload: JSON.stringify(input), at: Date.now() });\",\n\"  },\",\n```\n\nYou hold `db:schema`, so you author the project's tables too (`writeProjectTable`, above). If a\nhandler must write into a table that does not exist yet, create the table FIRST in the same turn,\nthen write the hook. Never write a handler that inserts into a table nobody has created — it throws\nat dispatch. Check the project's existing tables (`listProjectDir('database')`) before re-creating one.\n\nTo hand the event to an agent instead of writing code, use `trigger` (mutually exclusive\nwith `handler`): `{ type: 'event', on: { event: '<spaceId>/<name>' }, trigger: '<space>/<agent>#<action>' }`.\n\n### When the rule needs a MODEL, not a filter\n\nA code `handler` runs plain TypeScript with NO model — it can filter, reshape, and write\nrows, but it CANNOT reason, summarize, classify, draft, or decide. When the user explicitly\nasks for an AGENT to do something (\"have an agent write a one-line summary\", \"classify each\nitem\", \"draft a reply\"), you must actually invoke a model — never hand-roll a fake summary\nin string code (that silently produces garbage). Use `ctx.delegate` from a handler: it runs\nan agent headless, passes structured input, and RETURNS the result, which you write back with\n`ctx.db.update`. Delegate to a project/space agent when one fits; otherwise `user-thing/thing`\nis the always-available general agent:\n\n```typescript\n// Fires on project/db.tips.insert (payload = the row). A MODEL writes the summary.\nconst src = [\n  \"export default {\",\n  \"  type: 'event',\",\n  \"  on: { event: 'project/db.tips.insert' },\",\n  \"  handler: async ({ input, delegate, db }) => {\",\n  \"    const tip = input as { id: string; headline?: string; body?: string; summary?: string };\",\n  \"    if (tip.summary && tip.summary.trim()) return;\",     // idempotent: skip if already summarized\n  \"    const r = await delegate('user-thing/thing', undefined, {\",  // ctx.delegate(spaceRef, action?, opts) — agent = last path segment\n  \"      message: 'Write a single one-line summary (max 15 words) of this story tip. Reply with ONLY the summary line.',\",\n  \"      input: { headline: tip.headline, body: tip.body },\",\n  \"    });\",\n  \"    const summary = String((r && r.result) ?? '').trim().split('\\\\n')[0].slice(0, 200);\",\n  \"    if (summary) await db.update('tips', { where: { id: tip.id }, set: { summary } });\",\n  \"  },\",\n  \"};\",\n].join(\"\\n\");\nwriteProjectHook('summarize-tip', src);\n```\n\nThe handler writing `tips.summary` back does NOT re-fire itself — the loop guard excludes a\nhook's own writes (self-write exclusion), and the early `if (tip.summary) return` is a second\nguard. (You may equally use a `trigger` to a project/space agent when one already exists; the\n`ctx.delegate` form is preferred here because it lets you write the result back to the exact row.)\n\n## Database changes are events now\n\nThere is NO `{ type: 'database' }` hook. A project-db write is delivered as the event\n`project/db.<table>.<event>` (`event` ∈ `insert|update|remove`); the emitted payload IS\nthe written row. Subscribe with an event hook and (usually) a project `db` emitter def:\n\n```typescript\n// Producer: turn every insert into feed_items into a typed project event.\nconst evt = [\n  \"export default {\",\n  \"  type: 'db',\",\n  \"  on: { table: 'feed_items', event: 'insert' },\",\n  \"  emits: { 'item.added': { payload: { id: 'string', title: 'string' } } },\",\n  \"  emit: (row) => [{ event: 'item.added', payload: { id: row.row.id, title: row.row.title } }],\",\n  \"};\",\n].join(\"\\n\");\nwriteProjectEvent('feed-writes', evt);\n// Consumer: react to project/item.added (or directly to project/db.feed_items.insert).\n```\n\n## Scheduled polling — a `cron` EMITTER DEF (events/, with a `ctx.state` cursor)\n\nWhen the user wants to POLL a source on a schedule (\"every 30 minutes, check X for new items and\nstore them\"), author a `cron` EMITTER DEF with `writeProjectEvent` (it goes in `events/`, NOT\n`hooks/`). It has exactly one of `every` (`'<n>m|h|d'`) or `daily` (`'HH:MM'`), an async\n`emit(ctx)` that polls via `ctx.callConnection`, and a persisted `ctx.state` KV it uses as a\ncursor so a re-poll never re-emits an item it already saw. Pair it with a hook that stores each\nemitted item (the cron emit is PURE — it has NO `db`; it emits, a hook inserts):\n\n```typescript\n// events/poll-demo-source.ts — poll the demo source every 30m; ctx.state.lastId is the cursor.\nconst evt = [\n  \"export default {\",\n  \"  type: 'cron',\",\n  \"  every: '30m',\",                                  // EXACTLY one of every / daily\n  \"  connections: ['demo'],\",                         // the installed provider ctx.callConnection may reach\n  \"  emits: { 'source.item': { payload: { id: 'string', text: 'string' } } },\",\n  \"  async emit(ctx) {\",\n  \"    const since = (ctx.state && ctx.state['lastId']) || '0';\",   // persisted cursor\n  \"    let items = [];\",\n  \"    try { const res = await ctx.callConnection('demo', { method: 'GET', path: '/items', query: { since } });\",\n  \"          items = (res && res.data && res.data.items) || []; } catch { items = []; }\",\n  \"    if (ctx.state && items.length) ctx.state['lastId'] = String(items[items.length - 1].id);\",  // advance cursor → next tick sees only newer\n  \"    return items.map((it) => ({ event: 'source.item', payload: { id: String(it.id), text: String(it.text || '') } }));\",\n  \"  },\",\n  \"};\",\n].join(\"\\n\");\nwriteProjectEvent('poll-demo-source', evt);\n// Then a hook stores each polled item (do NOT re-declare an event the tips db emitter already owns):\nwriteProjectHook('store-polled-item', [\n  \"export default { type: 'event', on: { event: 'project/source.item' },\",\n  \"  handler: async ({ input, db }) => { const it = input; await db.insert('tips', { headline: String(it.text||'').slice(0,160), body: String(it.text||''), source: 'demo-poll', status: 'new', summary: '' }); } };\",\n].join(\"\\n\"));\n```\n\nThe `ctx.state` cursor is what makes a re-poll idempotent: because you advance `lastId` past every\nitem you emitted, the next tick's `since` skips them, so two consecutive runs never store the same\nitem twice. NEVER put a cron poll in a `handler` string that fabricates its own loop — use the def.\n\n## Cron hooks (scheduled AGENT run, not a poll)\n\nFor a scheduled AGENT action (not a source poll) a time-based HOOK uses `type: 'cron'`\n(`every: '<n>m|h|d'` or `daily: 'HH:MM'`) and a `trigger` (or `handler`):\n\n```typescript\nconst cron = [\n  \"export default { type: 'cron', every: '1d', trigger: 'system-appbuilder/app-architect#build_app' };\",\n].join(\"\\n\");\nwriteProjectHook('daily-refresh', cron);\n```\n\nGuidelines:\n\n- **The SCHEDULE is declared, never re-implemented in the body.** The host decides when a cron\n  hook is due (and, on boot, runs a window it missed while the pod was asleep — pods scale to\n  zero). So express the cadence in the DEF and let the handler do its work **every time it is\n  invoked**:\n\n  ```typescript\n  // ✅ weekly — declared. Fires on schedule, catches up a missed window, and a manual\n  //    \"run now\" (Studio / the hook-run endpoint) actually does the work.\n  \"export default { type: 'cron', every: '7d', trigger: 'kitchen/planner#weekly_plan' };\"\n\n  // ❌ NEVER: a daily cron that re-implements \"weekly\" by returning early on the wrong day.\n  //    It skips every catch-up run, and a manual run silently does nothing.\n  \"export default { type: 'cron', daily: '06:00', handler: async ({ db }) => {\",\n  \"  if (new Date().getDay() !== 0) return;   // ← the bug: the handler must not gate on the clock\",\n  ```\n\n  A handler may skip work that is genuinely already DONE (idempotence — \"this week's plan\n  already exists, nothing to do\"), but it must never refuse to run because of the wall clock.\n- Prefer a code `handler` over a `trigger` when the reaction is a simple filter/relay — no\n  agent, no LLM cost. But when the rule needs genuine reasoning (summarize/classify/draft/\n  decide), you MUST invoke a model — a `trigger` to an agent, or `ctx.delegate` from a\n  handler (see \"When the rule needs a MODEL\"). Never fake it with hand-written string logic.\n- Only list a provider in `connections:` that the user has installed; an unlisted provider\n  throws at call time.\n","numLines":778,"startLine":1,"totalLines":778}}}
