{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_V4RQ86q2cZVhuGSMwFTogi75","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tid: inventory\n3\toutput:\n4\t  scopes: array\n5\trole: explore\n6\tfunctions: []\n7\tprelude: |\n8\t  const documents = await Promise.all((attachmentIds as string[]).map((id) => readDocument(id)));\n9\t---\n10\t\n11\tPartition the supplied material into the real-world SUBJECTS a specialist should advise on. `request`,\n12\t`sourceSummary`, `attachmentIds`, and `specialistFacts` are in scope; the host has already read every\n13\tsupplied document into `documents`, and that source text is authoritative over the short summary.\n14\t\n15\tA specialist exists for ONE reason: to answer the user's LATER QUESTIONS with advice grounded in topic\n16\tknowledge — a place, a stage, a subject they will come back to and ASK about (\"what do I need to know\n17\tabout X?\", \"how does X work?\", \"what should I do for X?\"). So the test for every candidate scope is\n18\texactly that: **would the user come to it to ask for ADVICE?** If yes, it is a scope — one per distinct\n19\treal-world subject the material actually covers.\n20\t\n21\tA category of the user's own RECORDS is NEVER a scope — it is app DATA that lives in the project's\n22\ttables. Costs, expenses, a budget, payments, receipts, photos, memories, contacts, documents, bookings,\n23\ta list, a tracker, a dashboard, an overview, a \"summary/planner\" of everything: the user STORES and\n24\tVIEWS these, they do not ASK them for advice. Reject any candidate whose name is a record category, a\n25\tfile format, a data grouping, or a whole-material overview rather than a subject with its own knowledge\n26\tto teach. Every such fact instead becomes a row in the app's tables (built later) or background for the\n27\tsubject-scope that owns it.\n28\t\n29\tEnumerate one scope per distinct subject that has its own body of knowledge; combine adjacent parts that\n30\tserve one continuous purpose, and do not split a subject merely because it carries several kinds of\n31\trecords. Each supplied fact belongs to one scope only — never a child scope answerable by its parent.\n32\t\n33\tFor each scope, emit `{ topic, goal, research }`, where `research` is a JSON-stringifiable object\n34\twith `topic`, `executive_summary`, `findings`, `conclusion`, and `sources`. Ground its findings only\n35\tin the supplied document text and `specialistFacts`; sources must be empty because supplied material\n36\tis not web research. Emit ONE `currentTask.resolve({ scopes: [...] })` statement."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ddf06e51-7358-4abc-8049-dd6b1803b5d8","uuid":"1a6b50c6-7feb-4ade-b303-50245c862bb8","timestamp":"2026-07-16T06:49:23.005Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/libs/core/system-spaces/user-thing/tasklists/organize_material/01-inventory.md","content":"---\nid: inventory\noutput:\n  scopes: array\nrole: explore\nfunctions: []\nprelude: |\n  const documents = await Promise.all((attachmentIds as string[]).map((id) => readDocument(id)));\n---\n\nPartition the supplied material into the real-world SUBJECTS a specialist should advise on. `request`,\n`sourceSummary`, `attachmentIds`, and `specialistFacts` are in scope; the host has already read every\nsupplied document into `documents`, and that source text is authoritative over the short summary.\n\nA specialist exists for ONE reason: to answer the user's LATER QUESTIONS with advice grounded in topic\nknowledge — a place, a stage, a subject they will come back to and ASK about (\"what do I need to know\nabout X?\", \"how does X work?\", \"what should I do for X?\"). So the test for every candidate scope is\nexactly that: **would the user come to it to ask for ADVICE?** If yes, it is a scope — one per distinct\nreal-world subject the material actually covers.\n\nA category of the user's own RECORDS is NEVER a scope — it is app DATA that lives in the project's\ntables. Costs, expenses, a budget, payments, receipts, photos, memories, contacts, documents, bookings,\na list, a tracker, a dashboard, an overview, a \"summary/planner\" of everything: the user STORES and\nVIEWS these, they do not ASK them for advice. Reject any candidate whose name is a record category, a\nfile format, a data grouping, or a whole-material overview rather than a subject with its own knowledge\nto teach. Every such fact instead becomes a row in the app's tables (built later) or background for the\nsubject-scope that owns it.\n\nEnumerate one scope per distinct subject that has its own body of knowledge; combine adjacent parts that\nserve one continuous purpose, and do not split a subject merely because it carries several kinds of\nrecords. Each supplied fact belongs to one scope only — never a child scope answerable by its parent.\n\nFor each scope, emit `{ topic, goal, research }`, where `research` is a JSON-stringifiable object\nwith `topic`, `executive_summary`, `findings`, `conclusion`, and `sources`. Ground its findings only\nin the supplied document text and `specialistFacts`; sources must be empty because supplied material\nis not web research. Emit ONE `currentTask.resolve({ scopes: [...] })` statement.","numLines":36,"startLine":1,"totalLines":36}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_yzrcIXaZwLh8gpD6u61z4lHK","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tid: build_specialist\n3\toutput:\n4\t  topic: string\n5\t  ok: boolean\n6\t  errors: string\n7\tdependsOn: [inventory]\n8\tforEach: inventory.scopes\n9\trole: general\n10\tfunctions: []\n11\tcanDelegateTo:\n12\t  - system-architect/architect#synthesize_and_run\n13\t---\n14\t\n15\tBuild ONE specialist from an inventoried scope. `item` is `{ topic, goal, research }`. The supplied\n16\tmaterial is the source, so do not research. Emit exactly one self-contained statement: delegate to\n17\tthe architect with the item directly, then resolve the result without relying on a later statement or\n18\tcross-turn variable:\n19\t\n20\tcurrentTask.resolve(await delegate('system-architect', 'architect', 'synthesize_and_run', { query: 'Build a specialist space for ' + String(item.topic) + '.', context: { topic: String(item.topic), goal: String(item.goal), research: item.research } }).then((result) => { const built = (result && result.data) ? result.data : { ok: false, errors: 'the architect returned no result' }; return { topic: String(item.topic), ok: !!(result && result.ok === true && built.ok === true), errors: String(built.errors || '') }; }));"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ddf06e51-7358-4abc-8049-dd6b1803b5d8","uuid":"4f8220ff-c31f-43f9-8e28-ab41f1053224","timestamp":"2026-07-16T06:49:23.006Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/libs/core/system-spaces/user-thing/tasklists/organize_material/02-build_specialist.md","content":"---\nid: build_specialist\noutput:\n  topic: string\n  ok: boolean\n  errors: string\ndependsOn: [inventory]\nforEach: inventory.scopes\nrole: general\nfunctions: []\ncanDelegateTo:\n  - system-architect/architect#synthesize_and_run\n---\n\nBuild ONE specialist from an inventoried scope. `item` is `{ topic, goal, research }`. The supplied\nmaterial is